{"title_page": "Handball at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's qualification", "text_new": "{{other uses|Handball at the 2012 Summer Olympics (disambiguation)}}\nThe '''qualification for the [[Handball at the 2012 Summer Olympics|2012 Women's Olympic Handball Tournament]]''' is held from December 2010 to May 2012.\n{{TOCLimit|3}}\n\n==Qualification summary==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=75%\n|-\n! !! Date !! Venue !! Vacancies !! Qualified\n|-\n| Host Nation || || || align=\"center\"| 1 || {{hbw|GBR}}\n|-\n| [[2010 European Women's Handball Championship|2010 European Championship]] || 7\u201319 December 2010 || {{DEN}} & {{NOR}} || align=\"center\"| 1 || {{hbw|SWE}} <sup> [[#Notes1|*]] </sup>\n|-\n| 2011 Asian Olympic Qualification Tournament 2011 || 12\u201321 October || {{CHN}} || align=\"center\"| 1 || {{hbw|KOR}}\n|-\n| [[Handball at the 2011 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's tournament|2011 Pan American Games]] || 15\u201323 October 2011 || {{MEX}} || align=\"center\"| 1 || {{hbw|BRA}}\n|-\n| [[2011 World Women's Handball Championship|2011 World Championship]] || 2\u201318 December 2011 || {{BRA}} || align=\"center\"| 1 || {{hbw|NOR}}\n|-\n| [[2012 African Women's Handball Championship|2012 African Championship]] || 11\u201320 January 2012 || {{MAR}} || align=\"center\"| 1 || {{hbw|ANG}}\n|-\n| 2012 IHF Qualification Tournament #1 || 25\u201327 May 2012 || {{FRA}} || align=\"center\"| 2 || {{hbw|MNE}} <br /> {{hbw|FRA}}\n|-\n| 2012 IHF Qualification Tournament #2 || 25\u201327 May 2012 || {{ESP}} || align=\"center\"| 2 || {{hbw|ESP}} <br /> {{hbw|CRO}}\n|-\n| 2012 IHF Qualification Tournament #3 || 25\u201327 May 2012 || {{DEN}} || align=\"center\"| 2 || {{hbw|RUS}} <br /> {{hbw|DEN}}\n|-\n! Total !! colspan=\"2\"| !! 12 !!\n|}\n\n<div id=\"Notes1\"></div>\n:<sup> * </sup> Sweden qualified as 2010 European Championship runner up because Norway qualified as the 2011 World Champion.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Legend for qualification type\n|- bgcolor=#ccccff\n|Team qualified to the 2012 Olympic Tournament\n|-bgcolor=#ccffccc\n|Team qualified from the World Championship to the Olympic Qualification Tournament\n|-bgcolor=#ffffcc\n|Team qualified from Continental Events to the Olympic Qualification Tournament\n|}\n\n==World Championship==\n{{main article|2011 World Women's Handball Championship}}\n\nNotes: \n*The six best teams not yet qualified for the 2012 Olympic Games are qualified for one of the three World Olympic qualification tournaments (each one hosted by one of the three best teams).\n*Qualification to the Olympic qualification tournament through the World Championship supersedes qualification through the Continental Championship.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!width=40|Rank\n!width=180|Team\n|- bgcolor=#ccccff\n| {{Gold1}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|NOR}}\n|- bgcolor=#ccffccc\n| {{Silver2}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|FRA}}\n|- bgcolor=#ccffccc\n| {{Bronze3}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|ESP}}\n|- bgcolor=#ccffccc\n| 4\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|DEN}}\n|- bgcolor=#ccccff\n| 5\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|BRA}}\n|- bgcolor=#ccffccc\n| 6\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|RUS}}\n|- bgcolor=#ccffccc\n| 7\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|CRO}}\n|- bgcolor=#ccccff\n| 8\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|ANG}}\n|- bgcolor=#ccccff\n| 9\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|SWE}}\n|-bgcolor=#ccffccc\n| 10\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|MNE}}\n|- bgcolor=#ccccff\n| 11\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|KOR}}\n|-\n| 12\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|ISL}}\n|-bgcolor=#ffffcc\n| 13\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|ROU}}\n|-bgcolor=#ffffcc\n| 14\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|JPN}}\n|-bgcolor=#ffffcc\n| 15\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|NED}}\n|-\n| 16\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|CIV}}\n|-\n| 17\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|GER}}\n|-\n|-bgcolor=#ffffcc\n| 18\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|TUN}}\n|-\n| 19\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|KAZ}}\n|-\n| 20\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|URU}}\n|-\n| 21\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|CHN}}\n|-\n| 22\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|CUB}}\n|-bgcolor=#ffffcc\n| 23\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|ARG}}\n|-\n| 24\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|AUS}}\n|}\n\n==Continental qualification==\n\n===Europe (1st ranking continent)===\n{{main article|2010 European Women's Handball Championship}}\n\nNotes: \n*Norway is both European and World Champion, so Sweden goes directly to the Olympic Tournament in London on the European Champions spot.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!width=40|Rank\n!width=180|Team\n|- bgcolor=#ccccff\n| {{Gold1}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|NOR}}\n|- bgcolor=#ccccff\n| {{Silver2}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|SWE}}\n|-bgcolor=#ffffcc\n| {{Bronze3}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|ROU}}\n|-bgcolor=#ccffccc\n| 4\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|DEN}}\n|-bgcolor=#ccffccc\n| 5\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|FRA}}\n|-bgcolor=#ccffccc\n| 6\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|MNE}}\n|-bgcolor=#ccffccc\n| 7\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|RUS}}\n|-bgcolor=#ffffcc\n| 8\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|NED}}\n|-bgcolor=#ccffccc\n| 9\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|CRO}}\n|-\n| 10\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|HUN}}\n|-bgcolor=#ccffccc\n| 11\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|ESP}}\n|-\n| 12\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|UKR}}\n|-\n| 13\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|GER}}\n|-\n| 14\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|SRB}}\n|-\n| 15\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|ISL}}\n|-\n| 16\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|SLO}}\n|}\n\n===America (2nd ranking continent)===\n{{main article|Handball at the 2011 Pan American Games}}\n\n* Winner goes to the Olympic Tournament, the runner-up and third (since Australia placed 24th) go to one of the qualification tournament\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!width=40|Rank\n!width=180|Team\n|-bgcolor=#ccccff\n| {{Gold1}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|BRA}}\n|-bgcolor=#ffffcc\n| {{Silver2}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|ARG}}\n|-bgcolor=#ffffcc\n| {{Bronze3}}\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|DOM}}\n|-\n| 4\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|MEX}}\n|-\n| 5\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|CHI}}\n|-\n| 6\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|PUR}}\n|-\n| 7\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|URU}}\n|-\n| 8\n| align=\"left\"|{{hbw|USA}}\n|}\n\n===Africa (3rd ranking continent)===\n{{main article|