{"title_page": "Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman", "text_new": "{{short description|Hindu deity}}\n\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox deity\n| image       = Sowdamma.jpg\n| deity_of    = '''Kuladevatha of the Devanga People'''\n| mantra      = '' O\u1e43 Eesa Pathni sa Vithmahey Simha Twajaya dhimahi Thannoh Sowdi prachoday\u0101t'' (for Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman)  ''Om Sri Sri Sri Viraat Rupaya Mahamardini Tanno Chowdeshwari Prachodayat''  (for Chowdeshwari devi)\n| type        = [[Hindu]]\n| alt         = Sowdeswari amman\n| caption     = Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman<br>Sri Sowdeswari Devi\n| consort     = [[Shiva]] in the form of Ramalingeswara\n| weapon      = [[Trishula]]\n| mount       = [[Lion]] ([[Dawon]])\n| affiliation = [[Devi]][[Image:Om.svg|30px]]\n}}\n{{Infobox temple\n| map_type    = India Tamil Nadu#India\n| map_caption = Location in Tamil Nadu##Location in India\n| coordinates = {{coord|11|38|40.9|N|78|09|10.1|E|type:landmark_region:IN|display=inline,title}}\n| name        = Sri Ramalinga sowdeswari amman temple\n| country     = [[India]]\n| state       = [[Karnataka]], [[Telangana]], [[Andra Pradesh]], [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Kerala]], [[Odisha]], [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[Delhi]].\n| district    = All districts in [[Karnataka]], [[Tamil Nadu]] (mostly in [[Salem district|Salem]]), [[Kerala]] (mostly in [[Kuthampully Saree|Kuthampully]]), [[Andra Pradesh]] (especially in [[Nandavaram]]), [[Delhi]], [[Maharashtra]], and in some districts of other states.\n| location    = Temples are located all over India\n}}\n'''Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman''' is a Hindu deity, also known as [[Chowdeshwari Temple|Sri Chowdeshwari Devi]] ([[Hindi]] : \u0936\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u0930\u093e\u092e\u0932\u093f\u0902\u0917 \u091a\u094c\u0921\u0947\u0938\u094d\u0935\u0930\u0940 \u092e\u093e\u0924\u093e, [[Tamil language|Tamil]] : \u0bb8\u0bcd\u0bb0\u0bc0 \u0bb0\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bb2\u0bbf\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0b9a\u0bcc\u0b9f\u0bc7\u0bb8\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bb0\u0bbf\u0b85\u0bae\u0bcd\u0bae\u0ba9\u0bcd, [[Malayalam]] :\u0d36\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d40 \u0d30\u0d3e\u0d2e\u0d32\u0d3f\u0d02\u0d17 \u0d1a\u0d4c\u0d21\u0d47\u0d36\u0d4d\u0d35\u0d30\u0d3f \u0d05\u0d2e\u0d4d\u0d2e\u0d7b, [[Kannada]] : \u0cb6\u0ccd\u0cb0\u0cc0 \u0cb0\u0cbe\u0cae\u0cb2\u0cbf\u0c82\u0c97 \u0c9a\u0ccc\u0ca1\u0cc6\u0cb8\u0ccd\u0cb5\u0cbe\u0cb0\u0cbf \u0ca6\u0cc7\u0cb5\u0cbf, [[Telugu language|Telugu]]: \u0c36\u0c4d\u0c30\u0c40 \u0c30\u0c3e\u0c2e\u0c32\u0c3f\u0c02\u0c17 \u0c1a\u0c4c\u0c26\u0c46\u0c38\u0c4d\u0c35\u0c30\u0c3f \u0c26\u0c47\u0c35\u0c3f). This goddess is worshiped as Sri Chowdeshwari Devi or Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman in three forms: [[Shakti]], [[Chamunda]], and [[Jyoti (goddess)|Jyothi]] (the divine light). Her other names are [[Banashankari Amma Temple|Banashankari]] and Soodambigai. She is [[kuladevata|Kuladevatha]] of [[Devanga]] people.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/coimbatore/MGR-magic-still-spins-votes-from-Coimbatore-weavers/articleshow/52049522.cms|title=MGR magic still spins votes from Coimbatore weavers|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|access-date=2018-11-25}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAccording to the [[Devanga Purana]], Sage [[Devala]],is the progenitor of the Devanga community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.devangakula.org/puranas.html|title=Devanga Purana - \u0ba4\u0bc7\u0bb5\u0bbe\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95 \u0baa\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bbe\u0ba3\u0bae\u0bcd - Devalar - Devala Maharishi|website=Devangakula.org|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref>  He emerged from the third eye of [[Shiva|Lord Shiva]] (or, in some accounts, from Shiva's heart) to create clothing and to teach weaving to the world. When Devala returned after obtaining threads from [[Lord Vishnu]]'s lotus navel, a group of five demons, Vajramushti, Dhoomravakra, Dhoomratchasa, Chithrasena and Panchasena, attacked him at midnight. In the dark, the power of the demons was overwhelming. Devala attempted to fight them off using Vishnu's [[Sudarshana Chakra]], but failed, and finally prayed for [[Shakti]] to protect him. Shakti appeared in light and glory, wearing a bright full crown, holding a trident and other weapons in her hand while mounted on a lion. She killed the demons; their blood was white, black, red, green, and yellow. Devala soaked his threads in the demon's colorful blood. Shakti was then given the name [[Chowdeshwari Temple|Chowdeshwari]] or Sowdeswari (Chowda/Sowda/Sooda=the brightness). Sowdeswari advised Devala to worship her during every new moon (Amavasya).<ref name=\"devangakula.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.devangakula.org/AaadiAmavaasai.html|title=speciality of Aashada New Moon Day - \u0b86\u0b9f\u0bbf \u0b85\u0bae\u0bbe\u0bb5\u0bbe\u0b9a\u0bc8 \u0b9a\u0bbf\u0bb1\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1|website=Devangakula.org|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref> \n\nDevala went to the south [[Himalaya|Himalayas]] and founded Sagara Kingdom with Amodh Nagar as its capital. He wove new clothes and gave them to all: the gods ([[Trimurti]] and [[Tridevi]]), demigods ([[Deva (Hinduism)|Deva]], [[Asura]]), immortals ([[Gandarva]], [[Kinnara]]) and humans.\nDevala gave clothes to cover Deva's body parts so his community is named as [[Devanga]] (Anga=Body part) Community. He married [[Suryadev]]'s Sister DevaDhutta so as surya is first kinsmen , Then [[Shesha|Aadhi shesha]]'s daughter ChandraReka so Devanga people are called as Sedar/Jendar (Aadhi shesha is written as Aadhi Seda in tamil) and then he married Asura Vakrathantha's daughter AgniDhutta.People who follow Devala are known as [[Devanga]] or Devangar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.devangakula.org/DevalaMunivar.html|title=Devala munivar and avatars - \u0ba4\u0bc7\u0bb5\u0bb2 \u0bae\u0bc1\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0bb5\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bcd \u0b85\u0bb5\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bcd|website=Devangakula.org|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== In Tamil Nadu ==\nThe ancient [[Devanga]] community who worshipped the goddess in [[Karnataka]] dispersed to other states, including [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Andhra Pradesh]] and [[Kerala]]. They brought the weaving industry to their new home towns and set up temples of Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman as their deity. The Kannada-speaking Devanga community in Tamil Nadu is also known as Devanga Chettiar. They reside in a number of locations in the [[Coimbatore]], [[Theni]], [[Dindigul]], [[Salem district|Salem]], [[Erode]], [[Madurai]] and [[Virudhunagar]] districts. Although their religious practices fall into the [[Saivism]] and [[Vaishnavism]] denominations of Hinduism. they generally worship Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman. There are 10,000 Vamsa/Vansh clans in the Devanga community.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n==Chowdeshwari vs Ramalinga Sowdeswari==\nDevanga people originally followed [[Shaktism|Shaktism]] and worshipped the goddess in the form of [[Chowdeshwari Temple|Chowdeshwari]].King Devadas built a temple and invited Lord Shiva as Ramalingeshwara and Parvathi as Sowdeswari from Srisailam temple, after that they adopted some [[Hinduism|Hindu]] traditions, worshipping Chowdeshwari along with RamaBana ( [[Lord Ram]]'s Bow) and Lingam (Shiva), as Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman. In general the Devanga people <nowiki/> worship Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman as well as Chowdeshwari Devi, and several other names. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/view/erikaraisriramalingasowdeswari/home|title=Erikarai Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman Jalakandapuram|website=Sites.google.com}}</ref> while the Nepali Korakpur Devanga people worship her as Komalangi Devi.\n\n==Festivals==\n* Devanga new year: Those who follow the calendar of moon's rotation celebrate their new year on the day of [[Ugadi]]. If they follow the sun's rotation calendar, they celebrate their new year on the day of Chaithra 1. Most communities celebrate Ugadi as their new year.\n* Chaitra Suddha Panchami: This is the birthday celebration of Sage Devala. It is celebrated on the fifth Thithi day after Ugadi.\n* [[Ashadha]] [[Amavasya]]: This is the birthday celebration of the Goddess, commemorating Sowdeswari's rescue of Sage Devala and her conquest over the demons. It is celebrated on Amavasya of [[Ashadha]] month. The Devanga people also celebrate every [[Amavasya]] as their holy day, stopping weaving and offering prayers to Chowdeshwari.<ref name=\"devangakula.org\"/>\n* Devanga [[Janivara]]: Devanga people follow Rig [[Upakarma]] and therefore celebrate [[Janivara]] on the [[Shraavana]] Purnima (full moon day) of the traditional Hindu calendar, which is also the day of [[Raksha Bandhan]] in North India. It is known as Avani Avittam in Tamil Nadu and Kerala.\n* Yearly Festival (Varusha Habba): The yearly festival of Sowdeswari Amman Temple usually falls during the season of [[Navratri]] but varies depending on the tradition of the area. It includes [[Alagu Sevai]], Shakti [[Chamunda]] Jyothi pooja, Manja Neer Meravana, and Amman Beethi Ulaa. It is also known as Aikilu Habba.\n* [[Sankranti]]: Most Devanga people celebrate the Sankranti festival. In Tamil Nadu, they celebrate [[Pongal (festival)|Pongal]] instead of Sankranthi.\n*[[Diwali]]: Not all Devanga groups celebrate Diwali.  This varies by family tradition.\n* [[Janmastami]]: The Devanga people celebrate the Krishna Ashtami festival.\n* [[Ramnavami]]: As the Devanga pray to Lord Shiva in the form of Ramalingeshwar, they also celebrate Ramnavami.\n\nThe Devanga community flag is yellow, with the figures of Nandhi, Surya and Chandra depicted in green.\n\n==Pooja rituals in Sowdeswari Temple==\nThe [[Puja (Hinduism)|pooja]] rituals for Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman are a mixture of the culture of North and South India. The celebrants build a small cart-like building using jaggery, roof it with sugarcane and use Betel leaf for decoration. A special turmeric called pandaram is offered as [[Pras\u0101da]] for the deities. The Devanga people perform all their rituals by themselves.<ref>[https://sites.google.com/view/erikaraisriramalingasowdeswari/hom] {{dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Alagu seva ==\nThis ritual derives from the story that King Devadas, the seventh incarnation of Devala, built a beautiful temple for Sowdeshwari. He invited Lord Shiva and Parvathi from Srisailam to the temple but on the way Parvathi disappeared in the water as Devadas broke his promise. Devadas and his soldiers then wounded themselves with swords and suddenly the goddess appeared and joined them.<ref>[http://www.tamilvu.org/courses/degree/a061/a0614/html/a0614225.htm] {{dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref> The [[Alagu Sevai|alagu seva]] ritual commemorates this event and invokes Sowdeswari Amman. It is performed only by the [[Devanga]] people.<ref>[http://www.dinamani.com/edition_madurai/theni/2016/05/12/%E0%AE%B0%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%AE%E0%AE%B2%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%99%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%95-%E0%AE%9A%E0%AF%8C%E0%AE%9F%E0%AF%87%E0%AE%B8%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%B0%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%AF%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%AE%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%95/article3427842.ece] {{dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref> The holy turmeric mixture, pandaram, is applied to the wounds to protect them from infection. The celebrants, called veerakumars, strike their bare chests with holy swords in a ritual dance. The ritual is also called alagu seva or katthi haakkadhu.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.devangakula.org/AlaguSevai.html|title=\u0b85\u0bb2\u0b95\u0bc1 \u0b9a\u0bc7\u0bb5\u0bc8|website=Devangakula.org|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Alagu Veera Kumarargal.jpg|thumb|Alagu Veera Kumarargal (in front of Sri Chamundeshwari Temple, Mysuru)]]\n\n== Jagajathara Dhoddabba ==\nJagajathara Dhoddabba is a five-day [[festival]] celebrated for Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://peliharaburung.com/|title=Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman festival|website=Peliharaburung.com}}</ref>\n\nSakthi: It is dedicated to the goddess Sakthi \u2013 \"Irumaneru\" clan goddess will be revered for Sakthi function.\n\nChamundi: It is dedicated to the goddess Chamundeswari \u2013 \"Yendhelaaru\" clan goddess will be revered for Chamundi fucntion.\n\nJyothi: It is dedicated to goddess Jyothi Light \u2013 \"Ladhiyagaaru\" clan goddess will be revered for Maha Jyothi.\n\nGundam: The fourth day of the festival dedicated to the goddess Gundam \u2013 \"Kappelaaaru\" clan goddess will be revered for Gundam.<ref>[http://www.devangakula.org/DevangarFestivals.html] {{dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe famous chant slogan \"Shakthi Chamundi Jyothi amma Baa maa\" is used while invoking the goddesses.\n\n== Monasteries and temples ==\n====Hemakooda monastery ====\nThe Gayathri Peedam Hemakooda  (Hemakooda monastery) in [[Hampi (town)|Hampi]], Karnataka is led by Devanga Kula Jegath Guru Abbot Hampi Hemakooda Gayathri Peeda Sri Sri Sri [[Dhayananthapuri swamiji]], a leader of the [[Devanga]] community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.devangakula.org|title=About Devanga Guru|website=Devanga.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.devangaworld.com/en/node/166|title=Deavnga Guru and monastery|website=Devangaworld.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://yeddyurappa.in/cm-program-photos-24-1-2010/|title=Inaguration of Devanga bruhat Samavesha|website=Yeddyurappa.in}}</ref>\n[[File:Devanga guru.jpg|Dhayananthapuri swamiji-Hampi Hemakooda Gayathri Peedam, Devanga Guru|thumb|upright=0.3|right]]\n\n==== Sambusailam monastery ====\nThe Sambusailam monastery at [[Jalakandapuram]], Tamil Nadu is led by Devangakula Guru Abbot Chandramouleswara Swamiji.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.devangakula.org/|title=Devanga monastery details|website=Devanga.org}}</ref>\n[[File:Chandramouli swamjii.jpg|Chandramouleeswarar Swamji|thumb|upright=0.5|right]]\n\n=== Temples ===\nThe main temple to the goddess Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman is located in Hampi, Karnataka. It is known as Thai Sthalam (Mother Temple). The temple located in Dharapuram is also known as Thai Sthalam. There are many Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman temples in Tamil Nadu. In other states, the goddess is known as Sri Banashankari, Sri Chowdeswari, Sowdamman, or Soodambigai.\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book| last=Pintchman|first= Tracy|year =1994| url= https://books.google.com/books?id=XK7-r4hlcRYC| title= The Rise of the Goddess in the Hindu Tradition|publisher= SUNY Press, New York|isbn= 0-7914-2112-0}}\n*Census of India, 1961: Madras<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AuccAQAAMAAJ&q=sri+ramalinga+sowdeswari+amman&dq=sri+ramalinga+sowdeswari+amman&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjhlOPd2e_XAhXIRo8KHStuDOsQ6AEIJTAA|title=Census of India, 1961: Madras|first=India Office of the Registrar|last=General|date=15 June 1968|publisher=Manager of Publications|accessdate=15 June 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* Salem City, 1980<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sypuAAAAMAAJ&q=sowdeswari+amman&dq=sowdeswari+amman&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjSwOvt2-_XAhUESI8KHXznBowQ6AEIKjAB|title=Salem City: An Ethnohistory (1792-1992)|first1=Ka Ilakkumi|last1=N\u0101r\u0101ya\u1e47a\u1e49|first2=T.|last2=Gangadharan|first3=N.|last3=Chandrasekar|date=15 June 1999|publisher=Vysya college|accessdate=15 June 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* South India<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sEhJBfbhTAAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=sowdeswari+amman&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjSwOvt2-_XAhUESI8KHXznBowQ6AEIUDAJ#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Rough Guide to South India|first1=David|last1=Abram|first2=Rough|last2=Guides (Firm)|first3=Nick|last3=Edwards|date=15 June 2019|publisher=Rough Guides|accessdate=15 June 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n*2nd Congress on Traditional Sciences and Technologies of India, 27\u201331 December 1995, Anna University, Madras<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y0seAQAAMAAJ&q=sowdeswari+temple&dq=sowdeswari+temple&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwim8fCL8e_XAhUFTI8KHei2BBoQ6AEIKjAB|title=2nd Congress on Traditional Sciences and Technologies of India, 27th-31st December 1995, Anna University, Madras|first1=Anna|last1=University|first2=P. P. S. T.|last2=Foundation|date=15 June 1995|publisher=PPST Foundation|accessdate=15 June 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n*People of India<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kXHiAAAAMAAJ&q=sowdeswari+temple&dq=sowdeswari+temple&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwicoIin8e_XAhUDOY8KHbdIDTkQ6AEILzAC|title=People Of India: Tamil Nadu|first1=Kumar Suresh|last1=Singh|first2=R.|last2=Thirumalai|first3=S.|last3=Manoharan|date=30 January 1997|publisher=Affiliated East-West Press [for] Anthropological Survey of India|accessdate=15 June 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* Wangu, Madhu Bazaz (2003).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3SScwifhldQC|title=Images of Indian Goddesses: Myths, Meanings, and Models|publisher=Abhinav Publications|location=[[New Delhi]], India|isbn=81-7017-416-3}}</ref>\n*''Religions in the Modern World''<ref>{{Cite book|editor=Linda Woodhead|title=Religions in the Modern World|publisher=Routledge|edition=2nd|date=26 May 2009|isbn=978-0415458917}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2J04NHBI5Q '' Erikarai Sri Ramaliga sowdewswari amman'']\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BKR7OOCYauM&t=30s ''Jalakandapuram Kapelaru Festival'']\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=peebm-9GDa4&t=30s ''Guru Speech'']\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IzADGgg8slo&t=30s ''Guru meeting'']\n\n{{Shaktism}}\n\n[[Category:Consorts of Shiva]]\n[[Category:Hindu goddesses]]\n[[Category:Forms of Parvati]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Hindu deity}}\n\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox deity\n| image       = Sowdamma.jpg\n| deity_of    = '''Kuladevatha of the Devanga People'''\n| mantra      = '' O\u1e43 Eesa Pathni sa Vithmahey Simha Twajaya dhimahi Thannoh Sowdi prachoday\u0101t'' (for Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman)  ''Om Sri Sri Sri Viraat Rupaya Mahamardini Tanno Chowdeshwari Prachodayat''  (for Chowdeshwari devi)\n| type        = [[Hindu]]\n| alt         = Sowdeswari amman\n| caption     = Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman<br>Sri Sowdeswari Devi\n| consort     = [[Shiva]] in the form of Ramalingeswara\n| weapon      = [[Trishula]]\n| mount       = [[Lion]] ([[Dawon]])\n| affiliation = [[Devi]][[Image:Om.svg|30px]]\n}}\n{{Infobox temple\n| map_type    = India Tamil Nadu#India\n| map_caption = Location in Tamil Nadu##Location in India\n| coordinates = {{coord|11|38|40.9|N|78|09|10.1|E|type:landmark_region:IN|display=inline,title}}\n| name        = Sri Ramalinga sowdeswari amman temple\n| country     = [[India]]\n| state       = [[Karnataka]], [[Telangana]], [[Andra Pradesh]], [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Kerala]], [[Odisha]], [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[Delhi]].\n| district    = All districts in [[Karnataka]], [[Tamil Nadu]] (mostly in [[Salem district|Salem]]), [[Kerala]] (mostly in [[Kuthampully Saree|Kuthampully]]), [[Andra Pradesh]] (especially in [[Nandavaram]]), [[Delhi]], [[Maharashtra]], and in some districts of other states.\n| location    = Temples are located all over India\n}}\n'''Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman''' is a Hindu deity, also known as [[Chowdeshwari Temple|Sri Chowdeshwari Devi]] ([[Hindi]] : \u0936\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u0930\u093e\u092e\u0932\u093f\u0902\u0917 \u091a\u094c\u0921\u0947\u0938\u094d\u0935\u0930\u0940 \u092e\u093e\u0924\u093e, [[Tamil language|Tamil]] : \u0bb8\u0bcd\u0bb0\u0bc0 \u0bb0\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bb2\u0bbf\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0b9a\u0bcc\u0b9f\u0bc7\u0bb8\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bb0\u0bbf\u0b85\u0bae\u0bcd\u0bae\u0ba9\u0bcd, [[Malayalam]] :\u0d36\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d40 \u0d30\u0d3e\u0d2e\u0d32\u0d3f\u0d02\u0d17 \u0d1a\u0d4c\u0d21\u0d47\u0d36\u0d4d\u0d35\u0d30\u0d3f \u0d05\u0d2e\u0d4d\u0d2e\u0d7b, [[Kannada]] : \u0cb6\u0ccd\u0cb0\u0cc0 \u0cb0\u0cbe\u0cae\u0cb2\u0cbf\u0c82\u0c97 \u0c9a\u0ccc\u0ca1\u0cc6\u0cb8\u0ccd\u0cb5\u0cbe\u0cb0\u0cbf \u0ca6\u0cc7\u0cb5\u0cbf, [[Telugu language|Telugu]]: \u0c36\u0c4d\u0c30\u0c40 \u0c30\u0c3e\u0c2e\u0c32\u0c3f\u0c02\u0c17 \u0c1a\u0c4c\u0c26\u0c46\u0c38\u0c4d\u0c35\u0c30\u0c3f \u0c26\u0c47\u0c35\u0c3f). This goddess is worshiped as Sri Chowdeshwari Devi or Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman in three forms: [[Shakti]], [[Chamunda]], and [[Jyoti (goddess)|Jyothi]] (the divine light). Her other names are [[Banashankari Amma Temple|Banashankari]] and Soodambigai. She is [[kuladevata|Kuladevatha]] of [[Devanga]] people.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/coimbatore/MGR-magic-still-spins-votes-from-Coimbatore-weavers/articleshow/52049522.cms|title=MGR magic still spins votes from Coimbatore weavers|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|access-date=2018-11-25}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAccording to the [[Devanga Purana]], Sage [[Devala]],is the progenitor of the Devanga community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.devangakula.org/puranas.html|title=Devanga Purana - \u0ba4\u0bc7\u0bb5\u0bbe\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95 \u0baa\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bbe\u0ba3\u0bae\u0bcd - Devalar - Devala Maharishi|website=Devangakula.org|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref>  He emerged from the third eye of [[Shiva|Lord Shiva]] (or, in some accounts, from Shiva's heart) to create clothing and to teach weaving to the world. When Devala returned after obtaining threads from [[Lord Vishnu]]'s lotus navel, a group of five demons, Vajramushti, Dhoomravakra, Dhoomratchasa, Chithrasena and Panchasena, attacked him at midnight. In the dark, the power of the demons was overwhelming. Devala attempted to fight them off using Vishnu's [[Sudarshana Chakra]], but failed, and finally prayed for [[Shakti]] to protect him. Shakti appeared in light and glory, wearing a bright full crown, holding a trident and other weapons in her hand while mounted on a lion. She killed the demons; their blood was white, black, red, green, and yellow. Devala soaked his threads in the demon's colorful blood. Shakti was then given the name [[Chowdeshwari Temple|Chowdeshwari]] or Sowdeswari (Chowda/Sowda/Sooda=the brightness). Sowdeswari advised Devala to worship her during every new moon (Amavasya).<ref name=\"devangakula.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.devangakula.org/AaadiAmavaasai.html|title=speciality of Aashada New Moon Day - \u0b86\u0b9f\u0bbf \u0b85\u0bae\u0bbe\u0bb5\u0bbe\u0b9a\u0bc8 \u0b9a\u0bbf\u0bb1\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1|website=Devangakula.org|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref> \n\nDevala went to the south [[Himalaya|Himalayas]] and founded Sagara Kingdom with Amodh Nagar as its capital. He wove new clothes and gave them to all: the gods ([[Trimurti]] and [[Tridevi]]), demigods ([[Deva (Hinduism)|Deva]], [[Asura]]), immortals ([[Gandarva]], [[Kinnara]]) and humans.\nDevala gave clothes to cover Deva's body parts so his community is named as [[Devanga]] (Anga=Body part) Community. He married [[Suryadev]]'s Sister DevaDhutta so as surya is first kinsmen , Then [[Shesha|Aadhi shesha]]'s daughter ChandraReka so Devanga people are called as Sedar/Jendar (Aadhi shesha is written as Aadhi Seda in tamil) and then he married Asura Vakrathantha's daughter AgniDhutta.People who follow Devala are known as [[Devanga]] or Devangar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.devangakula.org/DevalaMunivar.html|title=Devala munivar and avatars - \u0ba4\u0bc7\u0bb5\u0bb2 \u0bae\u0bc1\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0bb5\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bcd \u0b85\u0bb5\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bcd|website=Devangakula.org|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== In Tamil Nadu ==\nThe ancient [[Devanga]] community who worshipped the goddess in [[Karnataka]] dispersed to other states, including [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Andhra Pradesh]] and [[Kerala]]. They brought the weaving industry to their new home towns and set up temples of Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman as their deity. The Kannada-speaking Devanga community in Tamil Nadu is also known as Devanga Chettiar. They reside in a number of locations in the [[Coimbatore]], [[Theni]], [[Dindigul]], [[Salem district|Salem]], [[Erode]], [[Madurai]] and [[Virudhunagar]] districts. Although their religious practices fall into the [[Saivism]] and [[Vaishnavism]] denominations of Hinduism. they generally worship Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman. There are 10,000 Vamsa/Vansh clans in the Devanga community.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n==Chowdeshwari vs Ramalinga Sowdeswari==\nDevanga people originally followed [[Shaktism|Shaktism]] and worshipped the goddess in the form of [[Chowdeshwari Temple|Chowdeshwari]].King Devadas built a temple and invited Lord Shiva as Ramalingeshwara and Parvathi as Sowdeswari from Srisailam temple, after that they adopted some [[Hinduism|Hindu]] traditions, worshipping Chowdeshwari along with RamaBana ( [[Lord Ram]]'s Bow) and Lingam (Shiva), as Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman. In general the Devanga people <nowiki/> worship Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman as well as Chowdeshwari Devi, and several other names. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/view/erikaraisriramalingasowdeswari/home|title=Erikarai Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman Jalakandapuram|website=Sites.google.com}}</ref> while the Nepali Korakpur Devanga people worship her as Komalangi Devi.\n\n==Festivals==\n* Devanga new year: Those who follow the calendar of moon's rotation celebrate their new year on the day of [[Ugadi]]. If they follow the sun's rotation calendar, they celebrate their new year on the day of Chaithra 1. Most communities celebrate Ugadi as their new year.\n* Chaitra Suddha Panchami: This is the birthday celebration of Sage Devala. It is celebrated on the fifth Thithi day after Ugadi.\n* [[Ashadha]] [[Amavasya]]: This is the birthday celebration of the Goddess, commemorating Sowdeswari's rescue of Sage Devala and her conquest over the demons. It is celebrated on Amavasya of [[Ashadha]] month. The Devanga people also celebrate every [[Amavasya]] as their holy day, stopping weaving and offering prayers to Chowdeshwari.<ref name=\"devangakula.org\"/>\n* Devanga [[Janivara]]: Devanga people follow Rig [[Upakarma]] and therefore celebrate [[Janivara]] on the [[Shraavana]] Purnima (full moon day) of the traditional Hindu calendar, which is also the day of [[Raksha Bandhan]] in North India. It is known as Avani Avittam in Tamil Nadu and Kerala.\n* Yearly Festival (Varusha Habba): The yearly festival of Sowdeswari Amman Temple usually falls during the season of [[Navratri]] but varies depending on the tradition of the area. It includes [[Alagu Sevai]], Shakti [[Chamunda]] Jyothi pooja, Manja Neer Meravana, and Amman Beethi Ulaa. It is also known as Aikilu Habba.\n* [[Sankranti]]: Most Devanga people celebrate the Sankranti festival. In Tamil Nadu, they celebrate [[Pongal (festival)|Pongal]] instead of Sankranthi.\n*[[Diwali]]: Not all Devanga groups celebrate Diwali.  This varies by family tradition.\n* [[Janmastami]]: The Devanga people celebrate the Krishna Ashtami festival.\n* [[Ramnavami]]: As the Devanga pray to Lord Shiva in the form of Ramalingeshwar, they also celebrate Ramnavami.\n\nThe Devanga community flag is yellow, with the figures of Nandhi, Surya and Chandra depicted in green.\n\n==Pooja rituals in Sowdeswari Temple==\nThe [[Puja (Hinduism)|pooja]] rituals for Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman are a mixture of the culture of North and South India. The celebrants build a small cart-like building using jaggery, roof it with sugarcane and use Betel leaf for decoration. A special turmeric called pandaram is offered as [[Pras\u0101da]] for the deities. The Devanga people perform all their rituals by themselves.<ref>[https://sites.google.com/view/erikaraisriramalingasowdeswari/hom] {{dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Alagu seva ==\nThis ritual derives from the story that King Devadas, the seventh incarnation of Devala, built a beautiful temple for Sowdeshwari. He invited Lord Shiva and Parvathi from Srisailam to the temple but on the way parvathi disappeared in the water as Devadas breaked his promise.Devadas and his soldiers then wounded themselves with swords and suddenly the goddess appeared and joined them.<ref>[http://www.tamilvu.org/courses/degree/a061/a0614/html/a0614225.htm] {{dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref> The [[Alagu Sevai|alagu seva]] ritual commemorates this event and invokes Sowdeswari Amman. It is performed only by the [[Devanga]] people.<ref>[http://www.dinamani.com/edition_madurai/theni/2016/05/12/%E0%AE%B0%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%AE%E0%AE%B2%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%99%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%95-%E0%AE%9A%E0%AF%8C%E0%AE%9F%E0%AF%87%E0%AE%B8%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%B0%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%AF%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%AE%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%95/article3427842.ece] {{dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref> The holy turmeric mixture, pandaram, is applied to the wounds to protect them from infection. The celebrants, called veerakumars, strike their bare chests with holy swords in a ritual dance. The ritual is also called alagu seva or katthi haakkadhu.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.devangakula.org/AlaguSevai.html|title=\u0b85\u0bb2\u0b95\u0bc1 \u0b9a\u0bc7\u0bb5\u0bc8|website=Devangakula.org|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Alagu Veera Kumarargal.jpg|thumb|Alagu Veera Kumarargal (in front of Sri Chamundeshwari Temple, Mysuru)]]\n\n== Jagajathara Dhoddabba ==\nJagajathara Dhoddabba is a five-day [[festival]] celebrated for Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://peliharaburung.com/|title=Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman festival|website=Peliharaburung.com}}</ref>\n\nSakthi: It is dedicated to the goddess Sakthi \u2013 \"Irumaneru\" clan goddess will be revered for Sakthi function.\n\nChamundi: It is dedicated to the goddess Chamundeswari \u2013 \"Yendhelaaru\" clan goddess will be revered for Chamundi fucntion.\n\nJyothi: It is dedicated to goddess Jyothi Light \u2013 \"Ladhiyagaaru\" clan goddess will be revered for Maha Jyothi.\n\nGundam: The fourth day of the festival dedicated to the goddess Gundam \u2013 \"Kappelaaaru\" clan goddess will be revered for Gundam.<ref>[http://www.devangakula.org/DevangarFestivals.html] {{dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe famous chant slogan \"Shakthi Chamundi Jyothi amma Baa maa\" is used while invoking the goddesses.\n\n== Monasteries and temples ==\n====Hemakooda monastery ====\nThe Gayathri Peedam Hemakooda  (Hemakooda monastery) in [[Hampi (town)|Hampi]], Karnataka is led by Devanga Kula Jegath Guru Abbot Hampi Hemakooda Gayathri Peeda Sri Sri Sri [[Dhayananthapuri swamiji]], a leader of the [[Devanga]] community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.devangakula.org|title=About Devanga Guru|website=Devanga.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.devangaworld.com/en/node/166|title=Deavnga Guru and monastery|website=Devangaworld.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://yeddyurappa.in/cm-program-photos-24-1-2010/|title=Inaguration of Devanga bruhat Samavesha|website=Yeddyurappa.in}}</ref>\n[[File:Devanga guru.jpg|Dhayananthapuri swamiji-Hampi Hemakooda Gayathri Peedam, Devanga Guru|thumb|upright=0.3|right]]\n\n==== Sambusailam monastery ====\nThe Sambusailam monastery at [[Jalakandapuram]], Tamil Nadu is led by Devangakula Guru Abbot Chandramouleswara Swamiji.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.devangakula.org/|title=Devanga monastery details|website=Devanga.org}}</ref>\n[[File:Chandramouli swamjii.jpg|Chandramouleeswarar Swamji|thumb|upright=0.5|right]]\n\n=== Temples ===\nThe main temple to the goddess Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman is located in Hampi, Karnataka. It is known as Thai Sthalam (Mother Temple). The temple located in Dharapuram is also known as Thai Sthalam. There are many Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman temples in Tamil Nadu. In other states, the goddess is known as Sri Banashankari, Sri Chowdeswari, Sowdamman, or Soodambigai.\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book| last=Pintchman|first= Tracy|year =1994| url= https://books.google.com/books?id=XK7-r4hlcRYC| title= The Rise of the Goddess in the Hindu Tradition|publisher= SUNY Press, New York|isbn= 0-7914-2112-0}}\n*Census of India, 1961: Madras<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AuccAQAAMAAJ&q=sri+ramalinga+sowdeswari+amman&dq=sri+ramalinga+sowdeswari+amman&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjhlOPd2e_XAhXIRo8KHStuDOsQ6AEIJTAA|title=Census of India, 1961: Madras|first=India Office of the Registrar|last=General|date=15 June 1968|publisher=Manager of Publications|accessdate=15 June 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* Salem City, 1980<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sypuAAAAMAAJ&q=sowdeswari+amman&dq=sowdeswari+amman&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjSwOvt2-_XAhUESI8KHXznBowQ6AEIKjAB|title=Salem City: An Ethnohistory (1792-1992)|first1=Ka Ilakkumi|last1=N\u0101r\u0101ya\u1e47a\u1e49|first2=T.|last2=Gangadharan|first3=N.|last3=Chandrasekar|date=15 June 1999|publisher=Vysya college|accessdate=15 June 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* South India<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sEhJBfbhTAAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=sowdeswari+amman&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjSwOvt2-_XAhUESI8KHXznBowQ6AEIUDAJ#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Rough Guide to South India|first1=David|last1=Abram|first2=Rough|last2=Guides (Firm)|first3=Nick|last3=Edwards|date=15 June 2019|publisher=Rough Guides|accessdate=15 June 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n*2nd Congress on Traditional Sciences and Technologies of India, 27\u201331 December 1995, Anna University, Madras<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y0seAQAAMAAJ&q=sowdeswari+temple&dq=sowdeswari+temple&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwim8fCL8e_XAhUFTI8KHei2BBoQ6AEIKjAB|title=2nd Congress on Traditional Sciences and Technologies of India, 27th-31st December 1995, Anna University, Madras|first1=Anna|last1=University|first2=P. P. S. T.|last2=Foundation|date=15 June 1995|publisher=PPST Foundation|accessdate=15 June 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n*People of India<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kXHiAAAAMAAJ&q=sowdeswari+temple&dq=sowdeswari+temple&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwicoIin8e_XAhUDOY8KHbdIDTkQ6AEILzAC|title=People Of India: Tamil Nadu|first1=Kumar Suresh|last1=Singh|first2=R.|last2=Thirumalai|first3=S.|last3=Manoharan|date=30 January 1997|publisher=Affiliated East-West Press [for] Anthropological Survey of India|accessdate=15 June 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* Wangu, Madhu Bazaz (2003).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3SScwifhldQC|title=Images of Indian Goddesses: Myths, Meanings, and Models|publisher=Abhinav Publications|location=[[New Delhi]], India|isbn=81-7017-416-3}}</ref>\n*''Religions in the Modern World''<ref>{{Cite book|editor=Linda Woodhead|title=Religions in the Modern World|publisher=Routledge|edition=2nd|date=26 May 2009|isbn=978-0415458917}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2J04NHBI5Q '' Erikarai Sri Ramaliga sowdewswari amman'']\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BKR7OOCYauM&t=30s ''Jalakandapuram Kapelaru Festival'']\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=peebm-9GDa4&t=30s ''Guru Speech'']\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IzADGgg8slo&t=30s ''Guru meeting'']\n\n{{Shaktism}}\n\n[[Category:Consorts of Shiva]]\n[[Category:Hindu goddesses]]\n[[Category:Forms of Parvati]]\n", "name_user": "Woodlot", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling, punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sri_Ramalinga_Sowdeswari_Amman"}
{"title_page": "Melody", "text_new": "{{about|melody Alison c  is the one who sing good sense day one also her sister Nathaly who has been by her side and in coraging to do her best\n\n{{redirect|Foreground (music)|more specific musical uses|Structural level}}\n{{short description|linear succession of musical tones in the foreground of a work of music}}\n\n[[File:BachFugueBar.png|thumb|A bar from [[Johann Sebastian Bach|J. S. Bach]]'s [[Fugue]] No. 17 in A-flat, [[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis|BWV]] 862, from ''[[The Well-Tempered Clavier]]'' (Part I), an example of [[counterpoint]].{{audio|BachFugueBar.mid|Play}} The two voices (melodies) on each [[staff (music)|staff]] can be distinguished by the direction of the [[Stem (music)|stems]] and [[beam (music)|beams]].<br />{{audio|BachFugueBar4.mid|Voice 4}}, {{audio|BachFugueBar3.mid|Voice 3}},<br />{{audio|BachFugueBar2.mid|Voice 2}}, {{audio|BachFugueBar1.mid|Voice 1}}]]\n\nA '''melody''' (from [[Greek language|Greek]] \u03bc\u03b5\u03bb\u1ff3\u03b4\u03af\u03b1, ''mel\u014did\u00eda'', \"singing, chanting\"),<ref>{{LSJ|melw{{!}}di/a|\u03bc\u03b5\u03bb\u1ff3\u03b4\u03af\u03b1|ref}}.</ref> also '''tune''', '''voice''' or '''line''', is a [[Linearity#Music|linear]] succession of musical tones that the listener perceives as a single entity. In its most literal sense, a melody is a combination of [[pitch (music)|pitch]] and [[rhythm]], while more figuratively, the term can include successions of other musical elements such as [[Timbre|tonal color]]. It may be considered the foreground to the background [[accompaniment]]. A line or [[part (music)|part]] need not be a foreground melody.\n\nMelodies often consist of one or more musical [[Phrase (music)|phrase]]s or [[Motif (music)|motifs]], and are usually repeated throughout a [[musical composition|composition]] in various forms. Melodies may also be described by their [[melodic motion]] or the pitches or the [[interval (music)|intervals]] between pitches (predominantly [[steps and skips|conjunct or disjunct]] or with further restrictions), pitch range, [[tension (music)|tension]] and release, continuity and coherence, [[cadence (music)|cadence]], and shape.\n\n{{quote|The true goal of music\u2014its proper enterprise\u2014is melody. All the parts of harmony have as their ultimate purpose only beautiful melody. Therefore, the question of which is the more significant, melody or harmony, is futile. Beyond doubt, the means is subordinate to the end.|[[Johann Philipp Kirnberger]] (1771)<ref>Forte, Allen (1979). ''Tonal Harmony in Concept & Practice'', p. 203. {{ISBN|0-03-020756-8}}.</ref>}}\n\n==Elements==\nGiven the many and varied elements and styles of melody \"many extant explanations [of melody] confine us to specific stylistic models, and they are too exclusive.\"<ref name=\"Kliewer\" /> Paul Narveson claimed in 1984 that more than three-quarters of melodic topics had not been explored thoroughly.<ref>Narveson, Paul (1984). ''Theory of Melody''. {{ISBN|0-8191-3834-7}}.</ref>\n\nThe melodies existing in most European music written before the 20th century, and popular music throughout the 20th century, featured \"fixed and easily discernible frequency [[Melodic pattern|patterns]]\", recurring \"events, often periodic, at all structural levels\" and \"recurrence of durations and patterns of durations\".<ref name=\"Kliewer\" />\n\nMelodies in the [[20th-century classical music|20th century]] \"utilized a greater variety of pitch resources than ha[d] been the custom in any other historical period of [[Western culture|Western]] [[Classical music|music]].\" While the [[diatonic scale]] was still used, the [[chromatic scale]] became \"widely employed.\"<ref name=\"Kliewer\">Kliewer, Vernon (1975). \"Melody: Linear Aspects of Twentieth-Century Music\", ''Aspects of Twentieth-Century Music'', pp. 270\u2013301. Wittlich, Gary (ed.). Englewood Cliffs, New Jersey: Prentice-Hall. {{ISBN|0-13-049346-5}}.</ref> Composers also allotted a structural role to \"the qualitative dimensions\" that previously had been \"almost exclusively reserved for pitch and rhythm\". Kliewer states, \"The essential elements of any melody are duration, pitch, and quality ([[timbre]]), texture, and loudness.<ref name=\"Kliewer\" /> Though the same melody may be recognizable when played with a wide variety of timbres and dynamics, the latter may still be an \"element of linear ordering.\"<ref name=\"Kliewer\" />\n\n==Examples==\n[[File:Pop Goes the Weasel melody.PNG|thumb|450px|\"[[Pop Goes the Weasel]]\" melody {{audio|Pop Goes the Weasel.ogg|Play}}]]\n[[File:Webern Variations melody.png|thumb|450px|Melody from [[Anton Webern]]'s Variations for orchestra, Op. 30 (pp. 23\u201324)<ref>Marquis, G. Weston (1964). ''Twentieth Century Music Idioms'', p. 2. Prentice-Hall, Inc., Inglewood Cliffs, New Jersey.</ref> {{audio|Webern Variations melody.mid|Play}}]]\nDifferent [[musical style]]s use melody in different ways. For example:\n*[[Jazz]] musicians use the term \"lead\" or \"head\" to refer to the main melody, which is used as a starting point for [[Musical improvisation|improvisation]].\n* [[Rock music]], and other forms of [[popular music]] and [[folk music]] tend to pick one or two melodies ([[Verse (popular music)|verse]] and [[refrain|chorus]], sometimes with a third, contrasting melody known as a [[Bridge (music)|bridge or middle eight]]) and stick with them; much variety may occur in the phrasing and [[lyrics]].\n*[[Indian classical music]] relies heavily on melody and [[rhythm]], and not so much on [[harmony]], as the music contains no chord changes.\n*[[Bali]]nese [[gamelan]] music often uses complicated variations and alterations of a single melody played simultaneously, called [[heterophony]].\n*In western [[classical music]], [[composer]]s often introduce an initial melody, or [[theme (music)|theme]], and then create variations. Classical music often has several melodic layers, called [[polyphony]], such as those in a [[fugue]], a type of [[counterpoint]]. Often, melodies are constructed from [[Motif (music)|motifs]] or short melodic fragments, such as the opening of Beethoven's Fifth Symphony. [[Richard Wagner]] popularized the concept of a ''[[leitmotif]]'': a motif or melody associated with a certain idea, person or place.\n*While in both most [[popular music]] and classical music of the [[common practice period]] pitch and duration are of primary importance in melodies, the [[contemporary music]] of the 20th and 21st centuries pitch and duration have lessened in importance and quality has gained importance, often primary. Examples include [[musique concr\u00e8te]], [[klangfarbenmelodie]], [[Elliott Carter]]'s ''Eight Etudes and a Fantasy'' (which contains a movement with only one note), the third movement of [[Ruth Crawford Seeger|Ruth Crawford-Seeger]]'s ''[[String Quartet 1931 (Crawford Seeger)|String Quartet 1931]]'' (later [[orchestration|re-orchestrated]] as ''Andante for string orchestra''), which creates the melody from an unchanging set of pitches through \"dissonant dynamics\" alone, and [[Gy\u00f6rgy Ligeti]]'s ''Aventures'', in which recurring [[phonetics]] create the linear form.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Hocket]]\n* [[Chord progression]]\n* [[Parsons code]], a simple notation used to identify a piece of music through [[melodic motion]]\u2014the motion of the [[Pitch (music)|pitch]] up and down.\n* [[Sequence (music)]]\n* [[Melody type]]\n* [[Unified field]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Willi Apel|Apel, Willi]]. ''Harvard Dictionary of Music'', 2nd ed., pp.&nbsp;517\u201319.\n*Edwards, Arthur C. ''The Art of Melody'', pp. xix\u2013xxx.\n* [[Imogen Holst|Holst, Imogen]](1962/2008). ''Tune'', Faber and Faber, London. {{ISBN|0-571-24198-0}}.\n* {{Interlanguage link multi|Joseph Smits van Waesberghe{{!}}Smits van Waesberghe, Joseph|nl|3=Jos. Smits van Waesberghe}} (1955). ''A Textbook of Melody: A course in functional melodic analysis'', American Institute of Musicology.\n* [[Bence Szabolcsi|Szabolcsi, Bence]] (1965). ''A History of Melody'', Barrie and Rockliff, London.\n* Trippett, David (2013). ''Wagner's Melodies''. Cambridge University Press.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Melody}}\n* {{wiktionary-inline|melody}}\n* {{wikiquote-inline}}\n* [http://www.americanmusicpreservation.com/carryatuneweek.htm Carry A Tune Week, list of tunes]\n* [http://www.northernsounds.com/forum/showthread.php/59076-Lesson-8-Melody-amp-Orchestration Creating and orchestrating a coherent and balanced melody]\n\n{{Melody|state=expanded}}\n{{Musical form}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Musical texture]]\n[[Category:Harmony]]\n[[Category:Melody| ]]\n[[Category:Polyphonic form]]\n[[Category:Formal sections in music analysis]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|melody in music|other senses of this word|Melody (disambiguation)}}\n{{redirect|Melodic}}\n{{redirect|Foreground (music)|more specific musical uses|Structural level}}\n{{short description|linear succession of musical tones in the foreground of a work of music}}\n\n[[File:BachFugueBar.png|thumb|A bar from [[Johann Sebastian Bach|J. S. Bach]]'s [[Fugue]] No. 17 in A-flat, [[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis|BWV]] 862, from ''[[The Well-Tempered Clavier]]'' (Part I), an example of [[counterpoint]].{{audio|BachFugueBar.mid|Play}} The two voices (melodies) on each [[staff (music)|staff]] can be distinguished by the direction of the [[Stem (music)|stems]] and [[beam (music)|beams]].<br />{{audio|BachFugueBar4.mid|Voice 4}}, {{audio|BachFugueBar3.mid|Voice 3}},<br />{{audio|BachFugueBar2.mid|Voice 2}}, {{audio|BachFugueBar1.mid|Voice 1}}]]\n\nA '''melody''' (from [[Greek language|Greek]] \u03bc\u03b5\u03bb\u1ff3\u03b4\u03af\u03b1, ''mel\u014did\u00eda'', \"singing, chanting\"),<ref>{{LSJ|melw{{!}}di/a|\u03bc\u03b5\u03bb\u1ff3\u03b4\u03af\u03b1|ref}}.</ref> also '''tune''', '''voice''' or '''line''', is a [[Linearity#Music|linear]] succession of musical tones that the listener perceives as a single entity. In its most literal sense, a melody is a combination of [[pitch (music)|pitch]] and [[rhythm]], while more figuratively, the term can include successions of other musical elements such as [[Timbre|tonal color]]. It may be considered the foreground to the background [[accompaniment]]. A line or [[part (music)|part]] need not be a foreground melody.\n\nMelodies often consist of one or more musical [[Phrase (music)|phrase]]s or [[Motif (music)|motifs]], and are usually repeated throughout a [[musical composition|composition]] in various forms. Melodies may also be described by their [[melodic motion]] or the pitches or the [[interval (music)|intervals]] between pitches (predominantly [[steps and skips|conjunct or disjunct]] or with further restrictions), pitch range, [[tension (music)|tension]] and release, continuity and coherence, [[cadence (music)|cadence]], and shape.\n\n{{quote|The true goal of music\u2014its proper enterprise\u2014is melody. All the parts of harmony have as their ultimate purpose only beautiful melody. Therefore, the question of which is the more significant, melody or harmony, is futile. Beyond doubt, the means is subordinate to the end.|[[Johann Philipp Kirnberger]] (1771)<ref>Forte, Allen (1979). ''Tonal Harmony in Concept & Practice'', p. 203. {{ISBN|0-03-020756-8}}.</ref>}}\n\n==Elements==\nGiven the many and varied elements and styles of melody \"many extant explanations [of melody] confine us to specific stylistic models, and they are too exclusive.\"<ref name=\"Kliewer\" /> Paul Narveson claimed in 1984 that more than three-quarters of melodic topics had not been explored thoroughly.<ref>Narveson, Paul (1984). ''Theory of Melody''. {{ISBN|0-8191-3834-7}}.</ref>\n\nThe melodies existing in most European music written before the 20th century, and popular music throughout the 20th century, featured \"fixed and easily discernible frequency [[Melodic pattern|patterns]]\", recurring \"events, often periodic, at all structural levels\" and \"recurrence of durations and patterns of durations\".<ref name=\"Kliewer\" />\n\nMelodies in the [[20th-century classical music|20th century]] \"utilized a greater variety of pitch resources than ha[d] been the custom in any other historical period of [[Western culture|Western]] [[Classical music|music]].\" While the [[diatonic scale]] was still used, the [[chromatic scale]] became \"widely employed.\"<ref name=\"Kliewer\">Kliewer, Vernon (1975). \"Melody: Linear Aspects of Twentieth-Century Music\", ''Aspects of Twentieth-Century Music'', pp. 270\u2013301. Wittlich, Gary (ed.). Englewood Cliffs, New Jersey: Prentice-Hall. {{ISBN|0-13-049346-5}}.</ref> Composers also allotted a structural role to \"the qualitative dimensions\" that previously had been \"almost exclusively reserved for pitch and rhythm\". Kliewer states, \"The essential elements of any melody are duration, pitch, and quality ([[timbre]]), texture, and loudness.<ref name=\"Kliewer\" /> Though the same melody may be recognizable when played with a wide variety of timbres and dynamics, the latter may still be an \"element of linear ordering.\"<ref name=\"Kliewer\" />\n\n==Examples==\n[[File:Pop Goes the Weasel melody.PNG|thumb|450px|\"[[Pop Goes the Weasel]]\" melody {{audio|Pop Goes the Weasel.ogg|Play}}]]\n[[File:Webern Variations melody.png|thumb|450px|Melody from [[Anton Webern]]'s Variations for orchestra, Op. 30 (pp. 23\u201324)<ref>Marquis, G. Weston (1964). ''Twentieth Century Music Idioms'', p. 2. Prentice-Hall, Inc., Inglewood Cliffs, New Jersey.</ref> {{audio|Webern Variations melody.mid|Play}}]]\nDifferent [[musical style]]s use melody in different ways. For example:\n*[[Jazz]] musicians use the term \"lead\" or \"head\" to refer to the main melody, which is used as a starting point for [[Musical improvisation|improvisation]].\n* [[Rock music]], and other forms of [[popular music]] and [[folk music]] tend to pick one or two melodies ([[Verse (popular music)|verse]] and [[refrain|chorus]], sometimes with a third, contrasting melody known as a [[Bridge (music)|bridge or middle eight]]) and stick with them; much variety may occur in the phrasing and [[lyrics]].\n*[[Indian classical music]] relies heavily on melody and [[rhythm]], and not so much on [[harmony]], as the music contains no chord changes.\n*[[Bali]]nese [[gamelan]] music often uses complicated variations and alterations of a single melody played simultaneously, called [[heterophony]].\n*In western [[classical music]], [[composer]]s often introduce an initial melody, or [[theme (music)|theme]], and then create variations. Classical music often has several melodic layers, called [[polyphony]], such as those in a [[fugue]], a type of [[counterpoint]]. Often, melodies are constructed from [[Motif (music)|motifs]] or short melodic fragments, such as the opening of Beethoven's Fifth Symphony. [[Richard Wagner]] popularized the concept of a ''[[leitmotif]]'': a motif or melody associated with a certain idea, person or place.\n*While in both most [[popular music]] and classical music of the [[common practice period]] pitch and duration are of primary importance in melodies, the [[contemporary music]] of the 20th and 21st centuries pitch and duration have lessened in importance and quality has gained importance, often primary. Examples include [[musique concr\u00e8te]], [[klangfarbenmelodie]], [[Elliott Carter]]'s ''Eight Etudes and a Fantasy'' (which contains a movement with only one note), the third movement of [[Ruth Crawford Seeger|Ruth Crawford-Seeger]]'s ''[[String Quartet 1931 (Crawford Seeger)|String Quartet 1931]]'' (later [[orchestration|re-orchestrated]] as ''Andante for string orchestra''), which creates the melody from an unchanging set of pitches through \"dissonant dynamics\" alone, and [[Gy\u00f6rgy Ligeti]]'s ''Aventures'', in which recurring [[phonetics]] create the linear form.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Hocket]]\n* [[Chord progression]]\n* [[Parsons code]], a simple notation used to identify a piece of music through [[melodic motion]]\u2014the motion of the [[Pitch (music)|pitch]] up and down.\n* [[Sequence (music)]]\n* [[Melody type]]\n* [[Unified field]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Willi Apel|Apel, Willi]]. ''Harvard Dictionary of Music'', 2nd ed., pp.&nbsp;517\u201319.\n*Edwards, Arthur C. ''The Art of Melody'', pp. xix\u2013xxx.\n* [[Imogen Holst|Holst, Imogen]](1962/2008). ''Tune'', Faber and Faber, London. {{ISBN|0-571-24198-0}}.\n* {{Interlanguage link multi|Joseph Smits van Waesberghe{{!}}Smits van Waesberghe, Joseph|nl|3=Jos. Smits van Waesberghe}} (1955). ''A Textbook of Melody: A course in functional melodic analysis'', American Institute of Musicology.\n* [[Bence Szabolcsi|Szabolcsi, Bence]] (1965). ''A History of Melody'', Barrie and Rockliff, London.\n* Trippett, David (2013). ''Wagner's Melodies''. Cambridge University Press.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Melody}}\n* {{wiktionary-inline|melody}}\n* {{wikiquote-inline}}\n* [http://www.americanmusicpreservation.com/carryatuneweek.htm Carry A Tune Week, list of tunes]\n* [http://www.northernsounds.com/forum/showthread.php/59076-Lesson-8-Melody-amp-Orchestration Creating and orchestrating a coherent and balanced melody]\n\n{{Melody|state=expanded}}\n{{Musical form}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Musical texture]]\n[[Category:Harmony]]\n[[Category:Melody| ]]\n[[Category:Polyphonic form]]\n[[Category:Formal sections in music analysis]]\n", "name_user": "2606:a000:1215:c375:74cb:2a13:30c5:d618", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melody"}
{"title_page": "RCGS Resolute", "text_new": "{{short description|Cruise ship}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin|display title=''RCGS Resolute''}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = RCGS Resolute.jpg\n| Ship caption = ''RCGS Resolute'' in [[Aberdeen]] in June 2019\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header = \n| Ship name = *''Society Adventurer'' (1991\u20131993)\n*''Hanseatic'' (1993\u20132018)\n*''RCGS Resolute'' (2018\u2013present)\n| Ship owner = * [[Discoverer Reederei]] (planned)<ref name=\"id\" />\n* Society Adventurer Shipping Company (1991\u20131993)<ref name=\"id\" /><ref group=\"note\">A fully-owned subsidiary of Rauma Yards</ref>\n* Bunnys Adventure & Cruise Shipping Co Ltd (1993\u2013present)<ref name=\"seaweb\" /><ref group=\"note\">A fully-owned subsidiary of [[Hanseatic Tours]] (later [[Hapag-Lloyd]])</ref>\n| Ship operator = * [[Hanseatic Tours]] (1993\u20131997)\n* [[Hapag-Lloyd Cruises]] (1997\u20132018)\n* [[One Ocean Expeditions]] (2018\u20132019)<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship registry = * [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]], {{BAH}} (1991\u20132018)\n* [[Madeira, Portugal|Madeira]], {{POR}} (2018\u2013present)<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship route = \n| Ship ordered = 22 December 1989<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship builder = [[Finnish maritime cluster|Rauma Yards]] ([[Rauma, Finland|Rauma]], [[Finland]])<ref name=\"id\">{{cite|last1=Id|first1=Kalle|last2=Peter|first2=Bruce|title=Innovation and Specialisation \u2014 A History of Shipbuilding in Finland|publisher=Nautilus|year=2017|ISBN=9788790924683|page=}}</ref>\n| Ship original cost = US$75 million<ref name=\"id\" />\n| Ship yard number =306<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship laid down = 3 September 1990<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship launched = 5 January 1991<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship completed = 7 June 1991<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship christened = \n| Ship acquired = \n| Ship maiden voyage = 27 March 1993.<ref name=\"fof\" />\n| Ship in service = \n| Ship out of service = \n|Ship identification=* [[Maritime call sign|Call sign]]: CQAL6\n* {{IMO Number|9000168}}\n* {{MMSI|255806208}}<ref name=\"equasis\">{{csr|register=E|id=9000168|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n* {{ship register|DNV|G99209}}<ref name=\"dnv\">{{csr|register=DNV|id=G99209|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n| Ship status = In service\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Header caption = <ref name=\"dnv\" /><ref name=\"Hapag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurolloyd.com/Hapag-Lloyd/HANSEATIC.pdf|title=MS ''Hanseatic'' Ship details|publisher=Hapag-Lloyd|accessdate=28 February 2009|format=PDF}}</ref>\n| Ship type = [[Cruise ship]]\n| Ship tonnage =* {{GT|8,445}}\n* {{NetT|2,573}}\n* {{DWT|1,177}}\n| Ship displacement = 5,892{{nbsp}}tonnes<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship length = {{convert|124.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship beam = {{convert|18.00|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship height = \n| Ship draught = \n| Ship draft = {{convert|4.9|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth = {{convert|7|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship decks = 6\n| Ship deck clearance = \n| Ship ramps = \n| Ship ice class = [[DNV GL]] E4<ref name=\"ice class\" group=\"note\" />\n| Ship power = 2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}[[MaK]] 8M453C (2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}2,940{{nbsp}}kW)<ref name=\"seaweb\">{{csr|register=SEAWEB|id=9000168|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n| Ship propulsion = Two shafts; [[controllable pitch propeller]]s\n| Ship speed = {{convert|16|kn}}\n| Ship range= {{convert|8600|nmi}}\n| Ship capacity = 184 passengers in 88 cabins and four suites\n| Ship crew = 125\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n\n'''''RCGS Resolute''''' is a [[star (classification)|five-star]] [[ice class|ice-strengthened]] expedition [[cruise ship]]. She was originally built as '''''Society Adventurer''''' in 1991, but after [[Discoverer Reederei]] was unable to take delivery of the vessel due to financial troubles, the completed ship was laid up at the shipyard for almost two years. She was acquired by [[Hanseatic Tours]] (later merged with [[Hapag-Lloyd]]) in 1993 and renamed '''''Hanseatic'''''. In 2018, she was chartered to [[One Ocean Expeditions]] and given her current name.\n\n== General characteristics ==\n\n''RCGS Resolute'' is {{convert|124.8|m|ftin}} [[length overall|long overall]] and {{convert|104.45|m|ftin}} [[length between perpendiculars|between perpendiculars]], has a beam of {{convert|18|m|ftin}} and draws {{convert|4.9|m|ftin}} of water with a [[Displacement (ship)|displacement]] of {{convert|5892|t|LT}}.<ref name=\"seaweb\" /> Her [[gross tonnage]] is 8,445; [[net tonnage]] 2,573; and [[deadweight tonnage]] 1,177 tonnes. The ship's hull and propulsion system are strengthened for navigation in ice-covered waters according to the [[DNV GL]] [[ice class]] E4.<ref name=\"dnv\" /><ref name=\"ice class\" group=\"note\">Equivalent to the highest [[Finnish-Swedish ice class]] for merchant ships, 1A Super</ref>\n\nBuilt to cater to the [[star (classification)|five-star]] luxury cruise market, interiors on the ''RCGS Resolute''{{'}}s six passenger-accessible decks were designed by the German architect [[Wilfried K\u00f6hnemann]].<ref name=\"id\" /> The vessel has 88 outside cabins and, above the bridge deck, four suites for a total of 184 passengers served by a crew of 125. Public spaces include a restaurant, multiple lounges, and a 78-seat theater. The ship carries 14 [[Zodiac inflatable boat]]s to take passengers ashore during expedition cruises.<ref name=\"Hapag\" /> \n\nThe ship's propulsion system consists of two [[straight-8 engine|eight-cylinder]] [[MaK]] 8M453C four-stroke medium-speed [[diesel engine]]s, each rated {{convert|2940|kW|hp}} at 600{{nbsp}}rpm, driving two [[controllable pitch propeller]]s. Onboard electrical power is generated by two {{convert|1160|kW|hp|adj=on}} [[straight-6 engine|six-cylinder]] MaK 6M332 auxiliary diesel generators and two {{convert|1040|kW|hp|adj=on}} main engine driven shaft generators. For maneuvering in ports, the ship has a {{convert|700|kW|hp|adj=on}} transverse [[bow thruster]].<ref name=\"seaweb\" /><ref name=\"dnv\" /> ''RCGS Resolute'' has a service speed of {{convert|16|kn}} and a cruising range of {{convert|8600|nmi}}.<ref name=\"Hapag\" />\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== ''Society Adventurer'' ===\n\nIn December 1989, the German cruise ship company [[Discoverer Reederei]] ordered a $75 million cruise ship from the Finnish shipbuilder [[Rauma Yards]] (formerly [[Rauma-Repola]]; later [[Finnyards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://meriteollisuus.teknologiateollisuus.fi/sites/meriteollisuus/files/inline-files/Meriteoll_historiikki_web.pdf|title=Kun rauta kelluu \u2014 V\u00e4l\u00e4hdyksi\u00e4 suomalaisen meriteollisuuden vuosisadasta|publisher=Meriteollisuus|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>) for its US-based subsidiary [[Society Expeditions]]. The ship, launched on 5 January 1991 as ''Society Adventurer'',<ref name=\"dnv\" /> was intended for adventure-style expedition cruises to remote destinations such as [[Antarctica]] and had, among other features, an ice-strengthened hull. However, Discoverer Reederei was unable to take delivery of the vessel in the following summer due to financial troubles and also had to cancel a [[sister ship]] that had already been contracted.<ref name=\"id\" /> As a result, the ownership of the vessel was transferred to Rauma Yards's newly-established Bahamas-registered subsidiary, Society Adventurer Shipping Company, on 7 June 1991.<ref name=\"dnv\" /> While on a lay-up at the yard, ''Society Adventurer'' was inspected by a number of parties interested in acquiring the vessel, among them the future [[president of the United States]] [[Donald Trump]] who visited Rauma in 1992.<ref name=\"id\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ls24.fi/uutiset/donald-trump-kavi-raumalla-laivakaupoilla-nayttelijavaimo-naytti-poseeraamisen-mallia|title=Donald Trump k\u00e4vi Raumalla laivakaupoilla - n\u00e4yttelij\u00e4vaimo n\u00e4ytti poseeraamisen mallia|work=L\u00e4nsi-Suomi|date=21 May 2016|accessdate=4 April 2020|language=fi}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.satakunnankansa.fi/satakunta/donald-trump-piipahti-1992-raumalla-laivakaupoilla-ja-tansseissa-13973980|title=Donald Trump piipahti 1992 Raumalla laivakaupoilla ja tansseissa|work=Satakunnan Kansa|date=9 November 2016|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Hanseatic'' ===\n[[File:Hanseatic 5.jpg|thumb|left|''Hanseatic'' sporting the classic [[Hamburg Atlantic Line]] livery in Nuuk, Greenland, in 2008.]]\n\nIn 1993, the ship was chartered and shortly afterwards purchased by the German expedition cruise operator [[Hanseatic Tours]].<ref name=\"id\" /> The company had been established two years earlier by [[Dirk Moldenhauer]], who had been the last captain of [[German Atlantic Line]]'s cruise ship [[TS Maxim Gorkiy|''Hanseatic'']] in 1973 and later acquired rights to the classic Hamburg Atlantic Line logo, livery and the name \"Hanseatic\".<ref name=\"simplonpc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.simplonpc.co.uk/HamburgAtlantik.html|title=Hamburg Atlantik Line/Deutsche Atlantik Line/Hanseatic Tours|accessdate=4 April 2020|author=Ian Boyle|work=Simplon Postcards}}</ref> ''Society Adventurer'' was renamed ''Hanseatic'' on 23 March 1993,<ref name=\"schwerdtner\">{{cite|title=German Luxury Ocean Liners: From Kaiser Wilhelm Der Grosse to Aidastella|last=Schwerdtner|first=Nils|publisher=Amberley Publishing|year=2013|}}</ref> becoming the fourth ship to bear the name, and the original blue-yellow-white Discoverer Reederei livery was replaced with the white hull and red decorative stripes.<ref name=\"id\" /> The vessel's maiden cruise from [[Hamburg]] to [[Sevilla]] began on 27 March 1993.<ref name=\"fof\">{{cite web|url=http://www.faktaomfartyg.se/society_adventurer_1991.htm|title=M/S Society Adventurer|work=Fakta om Fartyg|last=Asklander|first=Micke|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> When Hanseatic Tours was merged with [[Hapag-Lloyd Cruises]] in 1997, ''Hanseatic'' retained her original name as well as Hamburg Atlantic Line livery and funnel logo until rebranding in 2011.<ref name=\"schwerdtner\" /><ref name=\"seatrade\">{{cite web|url=https://www.seatrade-cruise.com/news-headlines/former-hanseatic-leaves-germany-after-long-career-hapag-lloyd|title=Former Hanseatic leaves Germany after long career with Hapag-Lloyd|work=Seatrade Cruise News|publisher=Informa Markets|date=8 October 2018|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n''Hanseatic'' remained in Hapag-Lloyd's fleet until 2018. Over the ship's 25-year career and a total of 667 cruises, she made 128 expeditions to Antarctica, two voyages to the [[Northern Sea Route]] (Northeast Passage), and transited the full length of the [[Northwest Passage]] 11 times.<ref name=\"seatrade\" /> The latter is a record number for passenger ships, exceeded only by the Russian [[icebreaker]] ''[[Kapitan Khlebnikov]]'' which is also used for expedition cruises.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spri.cam.ac.uk/resources/infosheets/northwestpassage.pdf|title=Transits of the Northwest Passage to the end of the 2019 navigation season|publisher=Scott Polar Research Institute|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> ''Hanseatic'' also holds the record for having been further north among passenger-carrying ships that are not icebreakers: on 26 August 2014, the vessel reached {{Coord|85|40.7|N|135|39.6|E|display=inline}}, {{convert|259|nmi}} from the [[North Pole]], due to unusually easy ice conditions in the Russian Arctic.<ref name=\"seatrade\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.travelpulse.com/news/cruise/expedition-ship-hanseatic-sets-new-record-for-passenger-ships.html|title=Expedition Ship Hanseatic Sets New Record for Passenger Ships|publisher=Travel Pulse|date=28 August 2014|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== ''RCGS Resolute'' ===\n\nIn June 2017, the Canada-based cruise ship operator [[One Ocean Expeditions]] announced that it would expand its fleet of expedition cruise ships with a long-term charter of the former ''Hanseatic''. The ship would be renamed ''RCGS Resolute'' after the 1850-built [[Royal Navy]] Arctic exploration vessel [[HMS Resolute|HMS ''Resolute'']] as well as the [[Inuit]] hamlet [[Resolute, Nunavut|Resolute]] in [[Nunavut]]. Furthermore, the ship would carry the initials of the [[Royal Canadian Geographic Society]] (RCGS) with whom One Ocean Expeditions had partnered.<ref name=\"oneocean_july2017\">{{cite web|url=https://discover.oneoceanexpeditions.com/rcgs-resolute/|title=One Ocean Expeditions Expands Fleet and Operations with New Vessel: RCGS RESOLUTE|publisher=One Ocean Expeditions|date=June 2017|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> After concluding her career with Hapag-Lloyd and a brief drydocking in Germany, the vessel headed to Canada in October 2018 under her new name and with new livery.<ref name=\"seatrade\" />\n\nIn 2019, the company's financial difficulties began to surface with the sudden withdrawal of the Russian research vessels ''[[Akademik Ioffe]]'' and ''[[Akademik Sergey Vavilov]]'' chartered from the [[Shirshov Institute of Oceanology]]. Although One Ocean Expeditions initially called the Russian owner's action a contract violation, it was later revealed that the company had failed to pay charter and fueling fees to the intermediate charterer Terragelida Ship Management which had then terminated the contract.<ref name=\"guardian_oct2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.pe.ca/business/regional-business/shipping-news-one-ocean-expeditions-sails-into-troubled-waters-370614/|title=SHIPPING NEWS: One Ocean Expeditions sails into troubled waters|date=31 October 2019|accessdate=5 April 2020|work=The Guardian|publisher=Saltwire Network}}</ref> This left One Ocean Expeditions with just one ship, ''RCGS Resolute''. In August, she was briefly arrested in [[Iqaluit]] over a C$100,000 payment dispute. While this issue was reportedly solved quickly,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.maritime-executive.com/article/cruise-ship-briefly-arrested-in-nunavut|title= Cruise Ship Briefly Arrested in Nunavut|publisher=The Maritime Executive|date=19 August 2019|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> another arrest over non-payment of services and crew wages followed in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] next month. Finally, in October One Ocean Expeditions was forced to cancel an Antarctic cruise midway after the vessel could not be refueled due to the company's non-payment of outstanding debts. Shortly after the ship's 140 passengers disembarked, ''RCGS Resolute'' was detained in [[Buenos Aires]] over \"significant debt\".<ref name=\"guardian_oct2018\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/one-ocean-expeditions-ship-detained-1.5370649|title=Ship belonging to troubled B.C. expedition cruise company detained in Argentina|date=24 November 2019|publisher=CBC|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> The company entered administration in January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cruisecritic.co.uk/news/4955/|title=One Ocean Expeditions Cruise Line Collapses|work=CruiseCritic|publisher=The Independent Traveler|date=13 January 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March 2020, ''RCGS Resolute'' left Buenos Aires after a total of US$3.6 million of outstanding debt was paid to fuel suppliers, ship agents and crew members.<ref name=\"chronicleherald17march\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thechronicleherald.ca/business/local-business/shipping-news-some-cruise-companies-scrap-schedule-others-continue-on-425502/|title=SHIPPING NEWS: Some cruise companies scrap schedule, others continue on|work=The Chronicle Herald|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Incidents ==\n\n=== 1996 grounding === \n\nOn 29 August 1996, ''Hanseatic'' ran aground in [[Simpson Strait]] in the Canadian Arctic. The vessel was eleven days into an eastbound transit along the Northwest Passage with 149 passengers and 110 crew, and had stopped at [[Gjoa Haven]] to let passengers ashore. Unknowingly to the crew, a green buoy marking a shallow shoal had not been removed after the previous navigating season and, over the winter months, had been moved to the northeast by about {{convert|200|m|yd}} by drifting ice. Shortly after departure, ''Hanseatic'' ran aground on the shoal at {{Coord|68|33.75|N|97|32.2|W|display=inline}}.<ref name=\"1996report\">{{cite web|url=https://bst-tsb.gc.ca/ENG/rapports-reports/marine/1996/m96h0016/M96H0016.pdf|title=Grounding of passenger vessel \"Hanseatic\" at Simpson Strait, Northwest Territories, 29 August 1996 (report number M96H0016)|publisher=Transport Safety Board of Canada|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWith no danger of the vessel sinking, ''Hanseatic''{{'}}s passengers were allowed to explore the nearby islands using the ship's boats until the Russian icebreaker ''[[Kapitan Dranitsyn]]'' arrived to pick up the passengers on 5 September and continue the Northwest Passage expedition under charter by Hanseatic Tours. ''Hanseatic'' itself was successfully refloated on 8 September. While the ship's hull was damaged during the grounding, no oil spilled to the sea and there were no injuries among the passengers or the crew.<ref name=\"1996report\" />\n\n=== 1997 grounding ===\n\nOn 14 July 1997, ''Hanseatic'' was grounded on a sand bank in [[Murchisonfjorden]] in [[Svalbard]] with 145 passengers onboard.<ref>{{cite book|title=Navigation Safety and Risk Assessment Challenges in the High North|last1=Marchenko|first1=N.|last2=Borch|first2=O.J.|last3=Andreassen|first3=N.|last4=Kuznetsova|first4=S.Yu.|last5=Ingimundarson|first5=V.|last6=Jakobsen|first6=U.|work=Marine Navigation: Proceedings of the 12th International Conference on Marine Navigation and Safety of Sea Transportation (TransNav 2017), June 21-23, 2017, Gdynia, Poland|publisher=CRC Press|year=2017|page=345|isbn=978-13-5158-218-6}}</ref><ref name=\"penguins\">{{cite book|last=Wright|first=Christopher|title=Of Penguins and Polar Bears: A History of Cold Water Cruising|year=2020|publisher=The History Press|ISBN=978-07-5099-456-9}}</ref> No injuries nor damage to the ship was reported, and the passengers were again taken to explore nearby islands on ''Hanseatic''{{'}}s Zodiac boats while awaiting evacuation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/0e7c429f30ac4d87307fb0eea3de2220|title=Cruise ship stuck in Arctic after running aground|date=14 July 1997|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> By 17 July, the ship had been refloated and was heading towards [[Longyearbyen]] for inspection.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.travelweekly.com/Cruise-Travel/Hanseatic-Grounded-in-the-Arctic|title=Hanseatic Grounded in the Arctic|date=17 July 1997|publisher=Travel Weekly|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 2005 grounding ===\n\nIn August 2005, ''Hanseatic'' ran aground near the island of [[Lur\u00f8ya, Nordland|Lur\u00f8ya]] on the Norwegian coast, just south of the [[Arctic Circle]], with 160 passengers onboard. While the vessel was not in danger of sinking despite a {{convert|5|m|ft|adj=on}} hole in one of her [[ballast water]] tank, the passengers and part of the crew was nonetheless evacuated.<ref name=\"penguins\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ranablad.no/nyheter/cruiseskip-evakuert/s/1-93-1706219|title=Cruiseskip evakuert|language=no|work=Rana Blad|date=22 August 2005|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013 drydock fire ===\n\nOn 13 June 2013, a fire broke out in ''Hanseatic''{{'}}s engine room due to [[hot work]] in one of the ballast water tanks while the ship was in a [[drydock]] at the Bredo Shipyard in [[Bremerhaven]]. Due to delays in drydocking and additional repairs required by the fire, four cruises between 17 June and 1 August had to be cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/travel/news/2013/06/25/hapag-lloyd-hanseatic-fire/2455171/|title=Hapag-Lloyd cancels more cruises due to shipyard fire|work=USA Today|date=25 June 2013|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 2020 collision with Venezuelan patrol boat ''Naiguat\u00e1'' ===\n[[File:Arbv GC23.jpg|thumb|right|Venezuelan Coast Guard patrol boat {{ship|Venezuelan patrol boat|Naiguat\u00e1||2}} (GC-23), which sank after ramming ''RCGS Resolute'', seen during sea trials in an undated photograph.]]\n\nOn 30 March 2020, ''RCGS Resolute'' was involved in an incident off the [[Venezuela]]n coast which led to the sinking of the [[Bolivarian Navy of Venezuela|Venezuelan Coast Guard]] patrol boat {{ship|Venezuelan patrol boat|Naiguat\u00e1||2}} (GC-23) following a collision with the cruise ship.<ref name=\"bbc3Apr2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-52151951|title=Venezuela navy vessel sinks after 'ramming cruise ship'|publisher=BBC News|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a statement by [[Columbia Cruise Services]] on 1 April, the company responsible for technical management of ''RCGS Resolute'', she was approached by ''Naiguat\u00e1'' in [[international waters]], about {{convert|13|nmi}} from [[La Tortuga Island]], shortly after midnight. The cruise ship, which had left Buenos Aires on 5 March,<ref name=\"chronicleherald17march\" /> had been adrift in the open sea for a day while carrying out routine maintenance on the starboard main engine before reaching her next destination, [[Willemstad]] in [[Cura\u00e7ao]]. After having questioned her intentions over radio, the Venezuelan Coast Guard vessel ordered ''RCGS Resolute'' to follow her to  [[Puerto Moreno]] on the eastern side of [[Margarita Island]]. While the master was in contact with the company's head office and [[designated person ashore]] (DPA), warning shots were fired from ''Naiguat\u00e1'' and, shortly afterwards, the Venezuelan patrol boat purposely rammed the cruise ship's starboard bow. During an apparent attempt of changing the heading of ''RCGS Resolute'' towards Venezuelan territorial waters, ''Naiguat\u00e1'' came in contact with the cruise ship's [[ice class|ice-strengthened]] [[bulbous bow]], started to take water, and eventually sank. The cruise ship, which had a crew of 32 onboard but was not carrying passengers, survived the encounter with superficial damage and remained on site for over an hour to provide assistance until being allowed to continue towards Willemstad by Maritime [[Rescue Coordination Centre]] (MRCC) Cura\u00e7ao.<ref name=\"ccs_statement\">{{cite  web|url=https://www.columbia-cs.com/statement-on-rcgs-resolute-incident/|title=Statement on RCGS RESOLUTE incident|publisher=Columbia Cruise Services|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nVenezuela, on the other hand, has accused ''RCGS Resolute'' of an act of \"aggression and piracy\" for intentionally ramming and sinking ''Naiguat\u00e1'' while the patrol boat was conducting a maritime traffic control operation, as well as of acting \"cowardly and criminal\" for not participating in the search and rescue of the patrol boat's crew of 44, all of which were rescued by another Venezuelan vessels.<ref name=\"bbc3Apr2020\" /><ref name=\"bnv_statement\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mindefensa.gob.ve/mindefensa/2020/03/31/comunicado-oficial-de-la-fuerza-armada-nacional-bolivariana-5/|title=Comunicado Oficial de la Fuerza Armada Nacional Bolivariana|language=Spanish|publisher=Ministry of Defense|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> An illustration of the incident released by the Venezuelan Navy describes''RCGS Resolute'' turning hard starboard to ram ''Naiguat\u00e1'' while the patrol boat was sailing alongside the cruise ship.<ref name=\"thedrive\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/32893/video-emerges-of-venezuelan-navy-ship-firing-on-and-colliding-with-cruise-ship-before-sinking|title=Video Emerges Of Venezuelan Navy Ship Firing On And Colliding With Cruise Ship Before Sinking|date=4 April 2020|publisher=The Drive|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> In addition, Venezuela has also alleged that Portuguese-flagged ''RCGS Resolute'' was carrying mercenaries for attacking the country's military bases and the ship's inflatable Zodiac boats were intended to transport them them to shore.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hisutton/2020/04/05/venezuelan-navy-retweets-questionable-evidence-in-resolute-case/#6363ebc77a2d|title=Venezuelan Navy Retweets Questionable \u2018Evidence\u2019 In Cruise Ship Case|publisher=Forbes|first=H.I.|last=Sutton|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nVideo footage released by the Venezuelan Navy first show a ''Naiguat\u00e1'' crewman firing warning shots with an [[AK-47]] assault rifle, followed by the patrol boat taking water while floating in front of ''RCGS Resolute''{{'}}s visibly damaged bow.<ref name=\"thedrive\" />\n\n{{-}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{commonscat|IMO 9000168}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Hapag-Lloyd Cruises}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:RCGS Resolute}}\n[[Category:Cruise ships]]\n[[Category:1991 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Rauma, Finland]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 2020]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Cruise ship}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin|display title=''RCGS Resolute''}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = RCGS Resolute.jpg\n| Ship caption = ''RCGS Resolute'' in [[Aberdeen]] in June 2019\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header = \n| Ship name = *''Society Adventurer'' (1991\u20131993)\n*''Hanseatic'' (1993\u20132018)\n*''RCGS Resolute'' (2018\u2013present)\n| Ship owner = * [[Discoverer Reederei]] (planned)<ref name=\"id\" />\n* Society Adventurer Shipping Company (1991\u20131993)<ref name=\"id\" /><ref group=\"note\">A fully-owned subsidiary of Rauma Yards</ref>\n* Bunnys Adventure & Cruise Shipping Co Ltd (1993\u2013present)<ref name=\"seaweb\" /><ref group=\"note\">A fully-owned subsidiary of [[Hanseatic Tours]] (later [[Hapag-Lloyd]])</ref>\n| Ship operator = * [[Hanseatic Tours]] (1993\u20131997)\n* [[Hapag-Lloyd Cruises]] (1997\u20132018)\n* [[One Ocean Expeditions]] (2018\u20132019)<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship registry = * [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]], {{BAH}} (1991\u20132018)\n* [[Madeira, Portugal|Madeira]], {{POR}} (2018\u2013present)<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship route = \n| Ship ordered = 22 December 1989<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship builder = [[Finnish maritime cluster|Rauma Yards]] ([[Rauma, Finland|Rauma]], [[Finland]])<ref name=\"id\">{{cite|last1=Id|first1=Kalle|last2=Peter|first2=Bruce|title=Innovation and Specialisation \u2014 A History of Shipbuilding in Finland|publisher=Nautilus|year=2017|ISBN=9788790924683|page=}}</ref>\n| Ship original cost = US$75 million<ref name=\"id\" />\n| Ship yard number =306<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship laid down = 3 September 1990<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship launched = 5 January 1991<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship completed = 7 June 1991<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship christened = \n| Ship acquired = \n| Ship maiden voyage = 27 March 1993.<ref name=\"fof\" />\n| Ship in service = \n| Ship out of service = \n|Ship identification=* [[Maritime call sign|Call sign]]: CQAL6\n* {{IMO Number|9000168}}\n* {{MMSI|255806208}}<ref name=\"equasis\">{{csr|register=E|id=9000168|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n* {{ship register|DNV|G99209}}<ref name=\"dnv\">{{csr|register=DNV|id=G99209|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n| Ship status = In service\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Header caption = <ref name=\"dnv\" /><ref name=\"Hapag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurolloyd.com/Hapag-Lloyd/HANSEATIC.pdf|title=MS ''Hanseatic'' Ship details|publisher=Hapag-Lloyd|accessdate=28 February 2009|format=PDF}}</ref>\n| Ship type = [[Cruise ship]]\n| Ship tonnage =* {{GT|8,445}}\n* {{NetT|2,573}}\n* {{DWT|1,177}}\n| Ship displacement = 5,892{{nbsp}}tonnes<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship length = {{convert|124.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship beam = {{convert|18.00|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship height = \n| Ship draught = \n| Ship draft = {{convert|4.9|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth = {{convert|7|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship decks = 6\n| Ship deck clearance = \n| Ship ramps = \n| Ship ice class = [[DNV GL]] E4<ref name=\"ice class\" group=\"note\" />\n| Ship power = 2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}[[MaK]] 8M453C (2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}2,940{{nbsp}}kW)<ref name=\"seaweb\">{{csr|register=SEAWEB|id=9000168|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n| Ship propulsion = Two shafts; [[controllable pitch propeller]]s\n| Ship speed = {{convert|16|kn}}\n| Ship range= {{convert|8600|nmi}}\n| Ship capacity = 184 passengers in 88 cabins and four suites\n| Ship crew = 125\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n\n'''''RCGS Resolute''''' is a [[star (classification)|five-star]] [[ice class|ice-strengthened]] expedition [[cruise ship]]. She was originally built as '''''Society Adventurer''''' in 1991, but after [[Discoverer Reederei]] was unable to take delivery of the vessel due to financial troubles, the completed ship was laid up at the shipyard for almost two years. She was acquired by [[Hanseatic Tours]] (later merged with [[Hapag-Lloyd]]) in 1993 and renamed '''''Hanseatic'''''. In 2018, she was chartered to [[One Ocean Expeditions]] and given her current name.\n\n== General characteristics ==\n\n''RCGS Resolute'' is {{convert|124.8|m|ftin}} [[length overall|long overall]] and {{convert|104.45|m|ftin}} [[length between perpendiculars|between perpendiculars]], has a beam of {{convert|18|m|ftin}} and draws {{convert|4.9|m|ftin}} of water with a [[Displacement (ship)|displacement]] of {{convert|5892|t|LT}}.<ref name=\"seaweb\" /> Her [[gross tonnage]] is 8,445; [[net tonnage]] 2,573; and [[deadweight tonnage]] 1,177 tonnes. The ship's hull and propulsion system are strengthened for navigation in ice-covered waters according to the [[DNV GL]] [[ice class]] E4.<ref name=\"dnv\" /><ref name=\"ice class\" group=\"note\">Equivalent to the highest [[Finnish-Swedish ice class]] for merchant ships, 1A Super</ref>\n\nBuilt to cater to the [[star (classification)|five-star]] luxury cruise market, interiors on the ''RCGS Resolute''{{'}}s six passenger-accessible decks were designed by the German architect [[Wilfried K\u00f6hnemann]].<ref name=\"id\" /> The vessel has 88 outside cabins and, above the bridge deck, four suites for a total of 184 passengers served by a crew of 125. Public spaces include a restaurant, multiple lounges, and a 78-seat theater. The ship carries 14 [[Zodiac inflatable boat]]s to take passengers ashore during expedition cruises.<ref name=\"Hapag\" /> \n\nThe ship's propulsion system consists of two [[straight-8 engine|eight-cylinder]] [[MaK]] 8M453C four-stroke medium-speed [[diesel engine]]s, each rated {{convert|2940|kW|hp}} at 600{{nbsp}}rpm, driving two [[controllable pitch propeller]]s. Onboard electrical power is generated by two {{convert|1160|kW|hp|adj=on}} [[straight-6 engine|six-cylinder]] MaK 6M332 auxiliary diesel generators and two {{convert|1040|kW|hp|adj=on}} main engine driven shaft generators. For maneuvering in ports, the ship has a {{convert|700|kW|hp|adj=on}} transverse [[bow thruster]].<ref name=\"seaweb\" /><ref name=\"dnv\" /> ''RCGS Resolute'' has a service speed of {{convert|16|kn}} and a cruising range of {{convert|8600|nmi}}.<ref name=\"Hapag\" />\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== ''Society Adventurer'' ===\n\nIn December 1989, the German cruise ship company [[Discoverer Reederei]] ordered a $75 million cruise ship from the Finnish shipbuilder [[Rauma Yards]] (formerly [[Rauma-Repola]]; later [[Finnyards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://meriteollisuus.teknologiateollisuus.fi/sites/meriteollisuus/files/inline-files/Meriteoll_historiikki_web.pdf|title=Kun rauta kelluu \u2014 V\u00e4l\u00e4hdyksi\u00e4 suomalaisen meriteollisuuden vuosisadasta|publisher=Meriteollisuus|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>) for its US-based subsidiary [[Society Expeditions]]. The ship, launched on 5 January 1991 as ''Society Adventurer'',<ref name=\"dnv\" /> was intended for adventure-style expedition cruises to remote destinations such as [[Antarctica]] and had, among other features, an ice-strengthened hull. However, Discoverer Reederei was unable to take delivery of the vessel in the following summer due to financial troubles and also had to cancel a [[sister ship]] that had already been contracted.<ref name=\"id\" /> As a result, the ownership of the vessel was transferred to Rauma Yards's newly-established Bahamas-registered subsidiary, Society Adventurer Shipping Company, on 7 June 1991.<ref name=\"dnv\" /> While on a lay-up at the yard, ''Society Adventurer'' was inspected by a number of parties interested in acquiring the vessel, among them the future [[president of the United States]] [[Donald Trump]].<ref name=\"id\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ls24.fi/uutiset/donald-trump-kavi-raumalla-laivakaupoilla-nayttelijavaimo-naytti-poseeraamisen-mallia|title=Donald Trump k\u00e4vi Raumalla laivakaupoilla - n\u00e4yttelij\u00e4vaimo n\u00e4ytti poseeraamisen mallia|work=L\u00e4nsi-Suomi|date=21 May 2016|accessdate=4 April 2020|language=fi}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.satakunnankansa.fi/satakunta/donald-trump-piipahti-1992-raumalla-laivakaupoilla-ja-tansseissa-13973980|title=Donald Trump piipahti 1992 Raumalla laivakaupoilla ja tansseissa|work=Satakunnan Kansa|date=9 November 2016|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Hanseatic'' ===\n[[File:Hanseatic 5.jpg|thumb|left|''Hanseatic'' sporting the classic [[Hamburg Atlantic Line]] livery in Nuuk, Greenland, in 2008.]]\n\nIn 1993, the ship was chartered and shortly afterwards purchased by the German expedition cruise operator [[Hanseatic Tours]].<ref name=\"id\" /> The company had been established two years earlier by [[Dirk Moldenhauer]], who had been the last captain of [[German Atlantic Line]]'s cruise ship [[TS Maxim Gorkiy|''Hanseatic'']] in 1973 and later acquired rights to the classic Hamburg Atlantic Line logo, livery and the name \"Hanseatic\".<ref name=\"simplonpc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.simplonpc.co.uk/HamburgAtlantik.html|title=Hamburg Atlantik Line/Deutsche Atlantik Line/Hanseatic Tours|accessdate=4 April 2020|author=Ian Boyle|work=Simplon Postcards}}</ref> ''Society Adventurer'' was renamed ''Hanseatic'' on 23 March 1993,<ref name=\"schwerdtner\">{{cite|title=German Luxury Ocean Liners: From Kaiser Wilhelm Der Grosse to Aidastella|last=Schwerdtner|first=Nils|publisher=Amberley Publishing|year=2013|}}</ref> becoming the fourth ship to bear the name, and the original blue-yellow-white Discoverer Reederei livery was replaced with the white hull and red decorative stripes.<ref name=\"id\" /> The vessel's maiden cruise from [[Hamburg]] to [[Sevilla]] began on 27 March 1993.<ref name=\"fof\">{{cite web|url=http://www.faktaomfartyg.se/society_adventurer_1991.htm|title=M/S Society Adventurer|work=Fakta om Fartyg|last=Asklander|first=Micke|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> When Hanseatic Tours was merged with [[Hapag-Lloyd Cruises]] in 1997, ''Hanseatic'' retained her original name as well as Hamburg Atlantic Line livery and funnel logo until rebranding in 2011.<ref name=\"schwerdtner\" /><ref name=\"seatrade\">{{cite web|url=https://www.seatrade-cruise.com/news-headlines/former-hanseatic-leaves-germany-after-long-career-hapag-lloyd|title=Former Hanseatic leaves Germany after long career with Hapag-Lloyd|work=Seatrade Cruise News|publisher=Informa Markets|date=8 October 2018|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n''Hanseatic'' remained in Hapag-Lloyd's fleet until 2018. Over the ship's 25-year career and a total of 667 cruises, she made 128 expeditions to Antarctica, two voyages to the [[Northern Sea Route]] (Northeast Passage), and transited the full length of the [[Northwest Passage]] 11 times.<ref name=\"seatrade\" /> The latter is a record number for passenger ships, exceeded only by the Russian [[icebreaker]] ''[[Kapitan Khlebnikov]]'' which is also used for expedition cruises.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spri.cam.ac.uk/resources/infosheets/northwestpassage.pdf|title=Transits of the Northwest Passage to the end of the 2019 navigation season|publisher=Scott Polar Research Institute|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> ''Hanseatic'' also holds the record for having been further north among passenger-carrying ships that are not icebreakers: on 26 August 2014, the vessel reached {{Coord|85|40.7|N|135|39.6|E|display=inline}}, {{convert|259|nmi}} from the [[North Pole]], due to unusually easy ice conditions in the Russian Arctic.<ref name=\"seatrade\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.travelpulse.com/news/cruise/expedition-ship-hanseatic-sets-new-record-for-passenger-ships.html|title=Expedition Ship Hanseatic Sets New Record for Passenger Ships|publisher=Travel Pulse|date=28 August 2014|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== ''RCGS Resolute'' ===\n\nIn June 2017, the Canada-based cruise ship operator [[One Ocean Expeditions]] announced that it would expand its fleet of expedition cruise ships with a long-term charter of the former ''Hanseatic''. The ship would be renamed ''RCGS Resolute'' after the 1850-built [[Royal Navy]] Arctic exploration vessel [[HMS Resolute|HMS ''Resolute'']] as well as the [[Inuit]] hamlet [[Resolute, Nunavut|Resolute]] in [[Nunavut]]. Furthermore, the ship would carry the initials of the [[Royal Canadian Geographic Society]] (RCGS) with whom One Ocean Expeditions had partnered.<ref name=\"oneocean_july2017\">{{cite web|url=https://discover.oneoceanexpeditions.com/rcgs-resolute/|title=One Ocean Expeditions Expands Fleet and Operations with New Vessel: RCGS RESOLUTE|publisher=One Ocean Expeditions|date=June 2017|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> After concluding her career with Hapag-Lloyd and a brief drydocking in Germany, the vessel headed to Canada in October 2018 under her new name and with new livery.<ref name=\"seatrade\" />\n\nIn 2019, the company's financial difficulties began to surface with the sudden withdrawal of the Russian research vessels ''[[Akademik Ioffe]]'' and ''[[Akademik Sergey Vavilov]]'' chartered from the [[Shirshov Institute of Oceanology]]. Although One Ocean Expeditions initially called the Russian owner's action a contract violation, it was later revealed that the company had failed to pay charter and fueling fees to the intermediate charterer Terragelida Ship Management which had then terminated the contract.<ref name=\"guardian_oct2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.pe.ca/business/regional-business/shipping-news-one-ocean-expeditions-sails-into-troubled-waters-370614/|title=SHIPPING NEWS: One Ocean Expeditions sails into troubled waters|date=31 October 2019|accessdate=5 April 2020|work=The Guardian|publisher=Saltwire Network}}</ref> This left One Ocean Expeditions with just one ship, ''RCGS Resolute''. In August, she was briefly arrested in [[Iqaluit]] over a C$100,000 payment dispute. While this issue was reportedly solved quickly,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.maritime-executive.com/article/cruise-ship-briefly-arrested-in-nunavut|title= Cruise Ship Briefly Arrested in Nunavut|publisher=The Maritime Executive|date=19 August 2019|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> another arrest over non-payment of services and crew wages followed in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] next month. Finally, in October One Ocean Expeditions was forced to cancel an Antarctic cruise midway after the vessel could not be refueled due to the company's non-payment of outstanding debts. Shortly after the ship's 140 passengers disembarked, ''RCGS Resolute'' was detained in [[Buenos Aires]] over \"significant debt\".<ref name=\"guardian_oct2018\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/one-ocean-expeditions-ship-detained-1.5370649|title=Ship belonging to troubled B.C. expedition cruise company detained in Argentina|date=24 November 2019|publisher=CBC|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> The company entered administration in January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cruisecritic.co.uk/news/4955/|title=One Ocean Expeditions Cruise Line Collapses|work=CruiseCritic|publisher=The Independent Traveler|date=13 January 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March 2020, ''RCGS Resolute'' left Buenos Aires after a total of US$3.6 million of outstanding debt was paid to fuel suppliers, ship agents and crew members.<ref name=\"chronicleherald17march\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thechronicleherald.ca/business/local-business/shipping-news-some-cruise-companies-scrap-schedule-others-continue-on-425502/|title=SHIPPING NEWS: Some cruise companies scrap schedule, others continue on|work=The Chronicle Herald|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Incidents ==\n\n=== 1996 grounding === \n\nOn 29 August 1996, ''Hanseatic'' ran aground in [[Simpson Strait]] in the Canadian Arctic. The vessel was eleven days into an eastbound transit along the Northwest Passage with 149 passengers and 110 crew, and had stopped at [[Gjoa Haven]] to let passengers ashore. Unknowingly to the crew, a green buoy marking a shallow shoal had not been removed after the previous navigating season and, over the winter months, had been moved to the northeast by about {{convert|200|m|yd}} by drifting ice. Shortly after departure, ''Hanseatic'' ran aground on the shoal at {{Coord|68|33.75|N|97|32.2|W|display=inline}}.<ref name=\"1996report\">{{cite web|url=https://bst-tsb.gc.ca/ENG/rapports-reports/marine/1996/m96h0016/M96H0016.pdf|title=Grounding of passenger vessel \"Hanseatic\" at Simpson Strait, Northwest Territories, 29 August 1996 (report number M96H0016)|publisher=Transport Safety Board of Canada|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWith no danger of the vessel sinking, ''Hanseatic''{{'}}s passengers were allowed to explore the nearby islands using the ship's boats until the Russian icebreaker ''[[Kapitan Dranitsyn]]'' arrived to pick up the passengers on 5 September and continue the Northwest Passage expedition under charter by Hanseatic Tours. ''Hanseatic'' itself was successfully refloated on 8 September. While the ship's hull was damaged during the grounding, no oil spilled to the sea and there were no injuries among the passengers or the crew.<ref name=\"1996report\" />\n\n=== 1997 grounding ===\n\nOn 14 July 1997, ''Hanseatic'' was grounded on a sand bank in [[Murchisonfjorden]] in [[Svalbard]] with 145 passengers onboard.<ref>{{cite book|title=Navigation Safety and Risk Assessment Challenges in the High North|last1=Marchenko|first1=N.|last2=Borch|first2=O.J.|last3=Andreassen|first3=N.|last4=Kuznetsova|first4=S.Yu.|last5=Ingimundarson|first5=V.|last6=Jakobsen|first6=U.|work=Marine Navigation: Proceedings of the 12th International Conference on Marine Navigation and Safety of Sea Transportation (TransNav 2017), June 21-23, 2017, Gdynia, Poland|publisher=CRC Press|year=2017|page=345|isbn=978-13-5158-218-6}}</ref><ref name=\"penguins\">{{cite book|last=Wright|first=Christopher|title=Of Penguins and Polar Bears: A History of Cold Water Cruising|year=2020|publisher=The History Press|ISBN=978-07-5099-456-9}}</ref> No injuries nor damage to the ship was reported, and the passengers were again taken to explore nearby islands on ''Hanseatic''{{'}}s Zodiac boats while awaiting evacuation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/0e7c429f30ac4d87307fb0eea3de2220|title=Cruise ship stuck in Arctic after running aground|date=14 July 1997|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> By 17 July, the ship had been refloated and was heading towards [[Longyearbyen]] for inspection.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.travelweekly.com/Cruise-Travel/Hanseatic-Grounded-in-the-Arctic|title=Hanseatic Grounded in the Arctic|date=17 July 1997|publisher=Travel Weekly|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 2005 grounding ===\n\nIn August 2005, ''Hanseatic'' ran aground near the island of [[Lur\u00f8ya, Nordland|Lur\u00f8ya]] on the Norwegian coast, just south of the [[Arctic Circle]], with 160 passengers onboard. While the vessel was not in danger of sinking despite a {{convert|5|m|ft|adj=on}} hole in one of her [[ballast water]] tank, the passengers and part of the crew was nonetheless evacuated.<ref name=\"penguins\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ranablad.no/nyheter/cruiseskip-evakuert/s/1-93-1706219|title=Cruiseskip evakuert|language=no|work=Rana Blad|date=22 August 2005|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013 drydock fire ===\n\nOn 13 June 2013, a fire broke out in ''Hanseatic''{{'}}s engine room due to [[hot work]] in one of the ballast water tanks while the ship was in a [[drydock]] at the Bredo Shipyard in [[Bremerhaven]]. Due to delays in drydocking and additional repairs required by the fire, four cruises between 17 June and 1 August had to be cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/travel/news/2013/06/25/hapag-lloyd-hanseatic-fire/2455171/|title=Hapag-Lloyd cancels more cruises due to shipyard fire|work=USA Today|date=25 June 2013|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 2020 collision with Venezuelan patrol boat ''Naiguat\u00e1'' ===\n[[File:Arbv GC23.jpg|thumb|right|Venezuelan Coast Guard patrol boat {{ship|Venezuelan patrol boat|Naiguat\u00e1||2}} (GC-23), which sank after ramming ''RCGS Resolute'', seen during sea trials in an undated photograph.]]\n\nOn 30 March 2020, ''RCGS Resolute'' was involved in an incident off the [[Venezuela]]n coast which led to the sinking of the [[Bolivarian Navy of Venezuela|Venezuelan Coast Guard]] patrol boat {{ship|Venezuelan patrol boat|Naiguat\u00e1||2}} (GC-23) following a collision with the cruise ship.<ref name=\"bbc3Apr2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-52151951|title=Venezuela navy vessel sinks after 'ramming cruise ship'|publisher=BBC News|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a statement by [[Columbia Cruise Services]] on 1 April, the company responsible for technical management of ''RCGS Resolute'', she was approached by ''Naiguat\u00e1'' in [[international waters]], about {{convert|13|nmi}} from [[La Tortuga Island]], shortly after midnight. The cruise ship, which had left Buenos Aires on 5 March,<ref name=\"chronicleherald17march\" /> had been adrift in the open sea for a day while carrying out routine maintenance on the starboard main engine before reaching her next destination, [[Willemstad]] in [[Cura\u00e7ao]]. After having questioned her intentions over radio, the Venezuelan Coast Guard vessel ordered ''RCGS Resolute'' to follow her to  [[Puerto Moreno]] on the eastern side of [[Margarita Island]]. While the master was in contact with the company's head office and [[designated person ashore]] (DPA), warning shots were fired from ''Naiguat\u00e1'' and, shortly afterwards, the Venezuelan patrol boat purposely rammed the cruise ship's starboard bow. During an apparent attempt of changing the heading of ''RCGS Resolute'' towards Venezuelan territorial waters, ''Naiguat\u00e1'' came in contact with the cruise ship's [[ice class|ice-strengthened]] [[bulbous bow]], started to take water, and eventually sank. The cruise ship, which had a crew of 32 onboard but was not carrying passengers, survived the encounter with superficial damage and remained on site for over an hour to provide assistance until being allowed to continue towards Willemstad by Maritime [[Rescue Coordination Centre]] (MRCC) Cura\u00e7ao.<ref name=\"ccs_statement\">{{cite  web|url=https://www.columbia-cs.com/statement-on-rcgs-resolute-incident/|title=Statement on RCGS RESOLUTE incident|publisher=Columbia Cruise Services|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nVenezuela, on the other hand, has accused ''RCGS Resolute'' of an act of \"aggression and piracy\" for intentionally ramming and sinking ''Naiguat\u00e1'' while the patrol boat was conducting a maritime traffic control operation, as well as of acting \"cowardly and criminal\" for not participating in the search and rescue of the patrol boat's crew of 44, all of which were rescued by another Venezuelan vessels.<ref name=\"bbc3Apr2020\" /><ref name=\"bnv_statement\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mindefensa.gob.ve/mindefensa/2020/03/31/comunicado-oficial-de-la-fuerza-armada-nacional-bolivariana-5/|title=Comunicado Oficial de la Fuerza Armada Nacional Bolivariana|language=Spanish|publisher=Ministry of Defense|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> An illustration of the incident released by the Venezuelan Navy describes''RCGS Resolute'' turning hard starboard to ram ''Naiguat\u00e1'' while the patrol boat was sailing alongside the cruise ship.<ref name=\"thedrive\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/32893/video-emerges-of-venezuelan-navy-ship-firing-on-and-colliding-with-cruise-ship-before-sinking|title=Video Emerges Of Venezuelan Navy Ship Firing On And Colliding With Cruise Ship Before Sinking|date=4 April 2020|publisher=The Drive|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> In addition, Venezuela has also alleged that Portuguese-flagged ''RCGS Resolute'' was carrying mercenaries for attacking the country's military bases and the ship's inflatable Zodiac boats were intended to transport them them to shore.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hisutton/2020/04/05/venezuelan-navy-retweets-questionable-evidence-in-resolute-case/#6363ebc77a2d|title=Venezuelan Navy Retweets Questionable \u2018Evidence\u2019 In Cruise Ship Case|publisher=Forbes|first=H.I.|last=Sutton|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nVideo footage released by the Venezuelan Navy first show a ''Naiguat\u00e1'' crewman firing warning shots with an [[AK-47]] assault rifle, followed by the patrol boat taking water while floating in front of ''RCGS Resolute''{{'}}s visibly damaged bow.<ref name=\"thedrive\" />\n\n{{-}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{commonscat|IMO 9000168}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Hapag-Lloyd Cruises}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:RCGS Resolute}}\n[[Category:Cruise ships]]\n[[Category:1991 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Rauma, Finland]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 2020]]\n", "name_user": "Tupsumato", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSociety Adventurer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RCGS_Resolute"}
